8 123 283\n| align=\"right\" | 27 510 066\n| align=\"right\" | 55 633 349\n| align=\"right\" | 67.84%\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | 65+\n| align=\"right\" | 3 170 132\n| align=\"right\" | 4 016 072\n| align=\"right\" | 7 186 204\n| align=\"right\" | 8.76%\n|-\n|}\n\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n== Immigration ==\n{{Main|Immigration to Turkey}}\n[[Immigration to Turkey]] is the process by which people [[human migration|migrate]] to [[Turkey]] to reside in the country. Many, but not all, become [[Turkish nationality law|Turkish citizens]]. After the  [[dissolution of the Ottoman Empire]] and following [[Turkish War of Independence]], an [[Emigration|exodus]] by the large portion of [[Turkish people|Turkish]] ([[Turkic peoples|Turkic]]) and [[Islam|Muslim]] peoples from the [[Balkans]] ([[Turks in the Balkans|Balkan Turks]], [[Albanians]], [[Bosniaks]], [[Pomaks]]), [[Caucasus]] ([[Abkhaz people|Abkhazians]], [[Ajarians]], '[[Circassians]]', [[Chechen people|Chechens]]), [[Crimea]] ([[Crimean Tatar diaspora]]), and [[Crete]] ([[Cretan Turks]]) took refuge in present-day Turkey and moulded the country's fundamental features. Trends of immigration towards Turkey continue to this day, although the motives are more varied and are usually in line with the patterns of global [[immigration]] movements &mdash; Turkey, for example, receives many economic migrants from nearby countries such as [[Armenia]], the [[Moldova]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Iran]], and [[Azerbaijan]], but also from [[Central Asia]]. [[Turkey's migrant crisis]] is a period during 2010s characterized by high numbers of people arriving in Turkey.\n\n== Internal migration ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|+ Place of origin (rows) versus place of residence (columns) for Turkish citizens in 2014<ref>TurkStat</ref>\n! <small>[[NUTS of Turkey|Regions]]</small>\n! <small>[[\u0130stanbul Region (statistical)|\u0130stanbul]]</small>\n! <small>[[West Marmara Region (statistical)|West Marmara]]</smal