29/agents-of-shield-season-3-spoilers-where-is-jemma/ |archivedate=September 30, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BellTHRDec2015\">{{cite web |url=http://edit.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/agents-shield-midseason-finale-death-846860 |title='Agents of SHIELD' EP Explains What's Next After That Shocking Midseason Finale Death |last=Bucksbaum |first=Sydney |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 8, 2015 |accessdate=December 11, 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6dhUjMD4x?url=http://edit.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/agents-shield-midseason-finale-death-846860 |archivedate=December 11, 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GreggSep2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/agents-shield-season-4-coulson-928375 |title='Agents of SHIELD' Season 4: Clark Gregg Teases Coulson's New Life After Demotion |last=Bucksbaum |first=Sydney |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=September 14, 2016 |accessdate=September 15, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6kWZQBfky?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/agents-shield-season-4-coulson-928375 |archivedate=September 14, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"PuzzleQuest\">{{cite web|url=https://news.marvel.com/games/60049/piecing-together-marvel-puzzle-quest-agent-coulson/ |title=PIECING TOGETHER MARVEL PUZZLE QUEST: AGENT COULSON |last=Chabala |first=Ben |publisher=[[Marvel Comics|Marvel.com]] |date=February 21, 2017 |accessdate=February 25, 2017 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6oXsnMvqa?url=https://news.marvel.com/games/60049/piecing-together-marvel-puzzle-quest-agent-coulson/ |archivedate=February 25, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CaptainMarvel\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/captain-marvel-cast-clark-gregg-returning-as-agent-coulson-1097356|title='Captain Marvel' Rounds Out Cast with Familiar Marvel Names|last=Couch|first=Aaron|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 26, 2018|accessdate=March 26, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326183143/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/captain-marvel-cast-clark-gregg-returning-as-agent-coulson-1097356|archivedate=March 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Feige/FilmJul2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/kevin-feige-interview-ant-man-and-the-wasp/|title=Kevin Feige Explains How They Planned \u2018Ant-Man and The Wasp\u2019 Alongside \u2018Infinity War,\u2019 the Disney Streaming Service and More [Interview]|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|publisher=[[/Film]]|date=July 6, 2018|accessdate=July 7, 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/70j2NMjzo?url=http://www.slashfilm.com/kevin-feige-interview-ant-man-and-the-wasp/|archivedate=July 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170221010220/http://www.imdb.com/character/ch0037737/ Agent Phil Coulson] on [[IMDb]]\n* {{Marveldatabase}}\n\n{{S.H.I.E.L.D.}}\n{{Marvel Cinematic Universe|selected=Cast}}\n{{Squadron Supreme}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coulson, Phil}}\n[[Category:Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Christopher Yost]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Matt Fraction]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 2012]]\n[[Category:Everyman]]\n[[Category:Fictional American secret agents]]\n[[Category:Fictional amputees]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 2008]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who became a protagonist in a spin-off]]\n[[Category:Fictional cyborgs]]\n[[Category:Fictional Iraq War veterans]]\n[[Category:Fictional murdered people in film]]\n[[Category:Fictional United States Army Rangers personnel]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Fictional principals and headteachers]]\n[[Category:Fictional spymasters]]\n[[Category:Male characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Male characters in film]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n[[Category:Marvel Cinematic Universe specific characters]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics television characters]]\n[[Category:S.H.I.E.L.D. agents]]\n[[Category:Superhero film characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fictional character from the Marvel Cinematic Universe}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color              = #AF181F\n| name               = Phil Coulson\n| series             = {{no italics|[[Marvel Cinematic Universe]]}}\n| image              = File:Phil Coulson in Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. .jpg\n| caption            = Clark Gregg as Phil Coulson in ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]''\n| first              = ''[[Iron Man (2008 film)|Iron Man]]'' (2008)\n| creator            = {{ubl|[[Mark Fergus and Hawk Ostby|{{ubl|Mark Fergus|Hawk Ostby}}]]|[[Art Marcum and Matt Holloway|{{ubl|Art Marcum|Matt Holloway}}]]}}\n| portrayer          = [[Clark Gregg]]\n| full_name          = Phillip J. Coulson<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tv.avclub.com/agents-of-s-h-i-e-l-d-s-fifth-season-ends-with-a-moving-1826121879 |title=Agents Of S.H.I.E.L.D.'s fifth season ends with a moving goodbye |last=McLevy |first=Alex |date=May 18, 2018 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |access-date=July 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| occupation         = [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]] Agent\n| nationality        = American\n}}\n'''Phillip J. Coulson''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|o\u028a|l|s|\u0259n}}) is a [[character (arts)|fictional character]] portrayed by [[Clark Gregg]] in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]]. A high-ranking member of the espionage agency [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]], he appeared in the films ''[[Iron Man (2008 film)|Iron Man]]'' (2008), ''[[Iron Man 2]]'' (2010), ''[[Thor (film)|Thor]]'' (2011), ''[[The Avengers (2012 film)|The Avengers]]'' (2012), and ''[[Captain Marvel (film)|Captain Marvel]]'' (2019). He also headlined the television series ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]'' (2013\u2013present), appeared in two [[Marvel One-Shots]] (both 2011), has been featured in various [[Marvel Cinematic Universe tie-in comics|tie-in comics]], and appeared in the digital series ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.: Slingshot]]'' (2016). The character also appears in other media, including [[American comic book|comics]] published by [[Marvel Comics]].\n\n==Marvel Cinematic Universe==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2018}}\n\n===Feature films===\n{{further|Iron Man (2008 film)|Iron Man 2|Thor (film)|The Avengers (2012 film)|Captain Marvel (film)}}\nAgent Coulson was introduced in the film ''Iron Man'', in which he attempts to debrief [[Tony Stark (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Tony Stark]] on his captivity in [[Afghanistan]]. He is one of several agents who accompany [[Pepper Potts]] in an attempt to arrest [[Iron Monger|Obadiah Stane]] once his criminal activities are revealed. In ''Iron Man 2'', Coulson is assigned to supervise Stark for a time before being reassigned to investigate a crisis in New Mexico. In both that film's [[post-credits scene]] and ''Thor'', Coulson's assignment is revealed to revolve around the discovery of [[Thor (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Thor]]'s [[Mjolnir (comics)|hammer]] in the New Mexico desert. Coulson is able to form an alliance between S.H.I.E.L.D. and Thor. In ''The Avengers'', Coulson is fatally wounded by [[Loki (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Loki]], which S.H.I.E.L.D. Director [[Nick Fury]] uses to motivate the [[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]].\n\n''Captain Marvel'', set in the 1990s, shows Coulson as a rookie agent of S.H.I.E.L.D. who works closely with Fury.\n\n===Tie-in comics===\n{{further|Marvel Cinematic Universe tie-in comics}}\nCoulson appears throughout the MCU tie-in comics in supporting roles, acting in the S.H.I.E.L.D. agent capacity that he does in the films.\n\n===Short films===\n{{further|Marvel One-Shots}}\nThe Marvel One-Shot ''[[Marvel One-Shots#The Consultant|The Consultant]]'' taking place after ''[[The Incredible Hulk (film)|The Incredible Hulk]],'' sees Coulson and [[Jasper Sitwell]] preventing [[Abomination (comics)|Emil Blonsky]] from being added to the Avengers roster. ''[[Marvel One-Shots#A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to Thor's Hammer|A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to Thor's Hammer]]'' shows Coulson getting into a scuffle on his way from Stark's lab in ''Iron Man 2'' to Thor's hammer in ''Thor''.\n\n===Television series===\n{{further|Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.}}\nIn ''Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.'', Coulson is revealed to be alive. He was brought back using the T.A.H.I.T.I project, which was meant to bring a dead Avenger back to life using a drug derived from an ancient [[Kree]] corpse. However, test patients developed psychosis and [[hypergraphia]], so Coulson had the project shut down.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Nothing Personal |episode-link=Nothing Personal (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=April 29, 2014 |season=1 |number=20}}</ref> Following Coulson's death, Fury resurrected him using T.A.H.I.T.I., despite the risks, and had Coulson's memories of the project replaced so that he could move on with a healthy life.<ref name=\"BeginningEnd\">{{Cite episode |title=Beginning of the End |episode-link=Beginning of the End (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=May 13, 2014 |season=1 |number=22}}</ref> Coulson puts together a team of agents, and they travel the world dealing with strange new cases.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Pilot |episode-link=Pilot (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=September 24, 2013 |season=1 |number=1}}</ref> During this time, [[Hydra (comics)|Hydra]] is [[Captain America: The Winter Soldier#Plot|revealed to have]] infiltrated S.H.I.E.L.D., leading to the latter's demise.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Turn, Turn, Turn |episode-link=Turn, Turn, Turn (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=April 8, 2014 |season=1 |number=17}}</ref> Fury makes Coulson the new Director of S.H.I.E.L.D. and tasks him with rebuilding the agency \"the right way\".<ref name=\"BeginningEnd\" />\n\nCoulson's involvement with alien materials leads to a faction of S.H.I.E.L.D. agents led by Robert Gonzalez who distrust secrets and the superhuman attempting to take over the fledgling organization, but Coulson convinces them to let him stay on as Director after helping [[Avengers: Age of Ultron|save hundreds of civilians]].<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Dirty Half Dozen |episode-link=The Dirty Half Dozen |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=April 28, 2015 |season=2 |number=19}}</ref> Together, they defeat a faction of [[Inhumans]], with Coulson losing a hand in the process.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=S.O.S. Part 2 |episode-link=S.O.S. (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=May 12, 2015 |season=2 |number=22}}</ref>\n\nCoulson later becomes romantically involved with Rosalind Price, the leader of an anti-Inhuman government taskforce called the Advanced Threat Containment Unit,<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Chaos Theory |episode-link=Chaos Theory (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=November 10, 2015 |season=3 |number=7}}</ref> until her death at the hands of [[Grant Ward (comics)|Grant Ward]], a Hydra agent who formerly worked with Coulson.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Closure |episode-link=Closure (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=December 1, 2015 |season=3 |number=9}}</ref> He gets revenge by crushing Ward's chest with his prosthetic hand.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Maveth |episode-link=Maveth |series=Marvels Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=December 8, 2015 |season=3 |number=10}}</ref> Following [[Captain America: Civil War#Plot|the signing of]] the [[Sokovia Accords]], S.H.I.E.L.D. is re-legitimized,<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Emancipation |episode-link=Emancipation (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=May 10, 2016 |season=3 |number=20}}</ref> with the still officially dead Coulson replaced as director by [[Jeffrey Mace]].<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Meet the New Boss |episode-link=Meet the New Boss (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=September 27, 2016 |season=4 |number=2}}</ref> Coulson allows himself to briefly become a [[Ghost Rider]] to defeat the artificial intelligence [[AIDA (comics)|Aida]].<ref>{{Cite episode |title=World's End |episode-link=World's End (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=May 16, 2017 |season=4 |number=22}}</ref>\n\nHe and his teammates are later abducted and sent to the future,<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Orientation Part 1 |episode-link=Orientation (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=December 1, 2017 |season=5 |number=1}}</ref> to prevent the extinction of humanity.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Rewind |episode-link=Rewind (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=December 22, 2017 |season=5 |number=4}}</ref> After their return, it is revealed that being Ghost Rider burned through the Kree DNA that healed Coulson's fatal injury, leaving him to die slowly.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Real Deal |episode-link=The Real Deal (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=March 9, 2018 |season=5 |number=12}}</ref> After the team's many failed attempts to save him, Coulson ultimately chooses to leave S.H.I.E.L.D. and live the remainder of his life in Tahiti with Melinda May with whom he developed a romantic relationship.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The End |episode-link=The End (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=May 18, 2018 |season=5 |number=22}}</ref>\n\nIn the sixth season, the team mourns Coulson. This is complicated, particularly for May and new Director [[Al MacKenzie|Mack]], by the arrival of the cold-blooded antagonist [[Sarge (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.)|Sarge]],<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Missing Pieces |episode-link=Missing Pieces (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=May 10, 2019 |season=6 |number=1}}</ref> who is physically and genetically identical to Coulson.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Window of Opportunity |episode-link=Window of Opportunity (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=May 17, 2019 |season=6 |number=2}}</ref>  They learn Sarge's body was created in an accident involving three reality-altering Monoliths, and was inhabited by the entity [[Pachakutiq (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.)|Pachakutiq]] thousands of years ago, losing both its and Coulson's memories.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Leap |episode-link=Leap (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=July 19, 2019 |season=6 |number=10}}</ref> Mack and Daisy kill Pachakutiq to avert the end of the world. When the team is then forced to escape an attack by the cybernetic alien Chronicoms, S.H.I.E.L.D. scientists Fitz and Simmons create an enhanced [[Life Model Decoy]] of Coulson to guide them in a journey through S.H.I.E.L.D.'s past, beginning in the 1930s.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=New Life |episode-link=New Life (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.) |series=Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |network=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=August 2, 2019 |season=6 |number=13}}</ref>\n\n===Digital series===\n{{further|Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.: Slingshot}}\nAfter stepping down as director of S.H.I.E.L.D. following [[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. (season 3)|season three]] of ''Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.'', Coulson appears in ''Slingshot'' to offer advice to S.H.I.E.L.D. asset [[Yo-Yo Rodriguez|Elena \"Yo-Yo\" Rodriguez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/tv/trailers/794811-watch-marvels-agents-of-shield-slingshot-in-full |title=Watch Marvel\u2019s Agents of SHIELD: Slingshot in Full! |publisher=[[ComingSoon.net]] |date=December 13, 2016 |accessdate=December 14, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6mk36H6DP?url=http://www.comingsoon.net/tv/trailers/794811-watch-marvels-agents-of-shield-slingshot-in-full |archivedate=December 14, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Concept and creation==\n{{Quote box|quote=Agent Coulson was one of the guys who wasn't really in the comic books, and he [had] a very kind of small role in ''Iron Man''. And I was just very lucky that they chose to expand that character and chose to put him more into the universe of it.|source=\u2014Gregg on the character's expansion in ''Thor''<ref name=\"MTVThor\"/>|width=33%|align=right}}\nPhil Coulson was created by [[Mark Fergus and Hawk Ostby|Mark Fergus, Hawk Ostby]], [[Art Marcum and Matt Holloway]] for ''Iron Man'', the first film in the MCU.<ref name=\"April2006Variety\" /><ref name=\"FergusOstbyIM\" /> Coulson was the first S.H.I.E.L.D. agent introduced in the MCU, and was portrayed by [[Clark Gregg]], who was offered a three-picture deal. Gregg initially balked at this due to the character only being known as \"Agent\" and having few lines, but recognized Marvel's plan for an interconnected universe.<ref name=\"GreggJan2016\" /> Gregg went on to play the character in ''[[Iron Man 2]]'', ''[[Thor (film)|Thor]]'', and ''[[The Avengers (2012 film)|The Avengers]]''.<ref name=\"shorts\" />\n\nThroughout the films, Coulson is generally depicted as a supporting character of the protagonists and used to represent S.H.I.E.L.D.'s presence, to the point that Gregg has described Coulson as \"''the'' S.H.I.E.L.D. agent\". However, for the [[Marvel One-Shot]] short films ''[[Marvel One-Shots#The Consultant (2011)|The Consultant]]'' and ''[[Marvel One-Shots#A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to Thor's Hammer (2011)|A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to Thor's Hammer]]'', Coulson is given \"a chance to stand in his own spotlight for once\". This was a \"natural\" move for co-producer Brad Winderbaum, who wanted to \"paint a picture of S.H.I.E.L.D. pulling the strings and being responsible for some of the events we've seen in the films. What better character to represent this idea than Agent Coulson, the first S.H.I.E.L.D. agent we were introduced to?\"<ref name=\"shorts\"/>\n\nAt the 2012 [[New York Comic Con]], [[Joss Whedon]] and [[Kevin Feige]] announced that Gregg would be starring as Coulson in ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]'', despite the character dying in ''The Avengers'', with Whedon saying \"He's headlining the S.H.I.E.L.D. show and always was.\"<ref name=\"NYCC2012\" /> Gregg said of Whedon's explanation for Coulson's resurrection, \"I found it so fascinating and so true to the world of the comics and mythology in general as I understand them that I was immediately in.\"<ref name=\"GreggScreenRantApr2013\" /> Regarding the amount of creative input he has over the character in the series, Gregg said, \"I have meetings with [the [[showrunner]]s] once or twice a year and talk about what the big ideas are ... They're really responsive to the fact that I've been involved with this person four, five years longer than them, but ... I have no complaints with what they're doing.\"<ref name=\"GreggCBRJan2015\" />\n\n''Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.'' costume designer Ann Foley described Coulson as a \"company man\", wearing suits in \"the S.H.I.E.L.D. palette\u2014grey, black and navy with a distinct but subtle pattern.\" Foley did note \"subtle changes\" in Coulson's costuming in the series from the films, such as streamlined suits and \"more slick\" ties, \"now that [he] is back after being 'killed' by Loki\".<ref name=\"FoleyTyranny\" /> After Coulson's hand is cut off in the second-season finale, which was realized by having a mechanical axe cut through a \"faux arm made of tripe wrapped around a chicken thigh\", Gregg described it as \"heavy ... one of those things where you\u2019re having the practical difficulty your character does. People were handing me stuff, like files, and I couldn\u2019t really open them without using my nose.\"<ref name=\"CoulsonArm\" /> This practicality issue continued with the prosthetic hand Coulson subsequently has to use, with Gregg saying \"the reality informs the thing. It\u2019s really hard to figure out how to use this prosthetic, and that\u2019s what Phil Coulson\u2019s going through ... I\u2019m hoping it evolves at some point.\"<ref name=\"TCAParty2015\" /> Gregg also noted that in the third season Coulson would be wearing more casual clothes, partly because \"he can\u2019t even seem to tie a tie\" with his new hand.<ref name=\"CoulsonCasual\" /> The prosthetic hand evolves throughout the season, with a later iteration projecting an energy shield, inspired by [[Captain America's shield#Other shields|a similar one]] used in the comics by [[Captain America]].<ref name=\"CoulsonShield\" /> The energy shield was created by Cosa, one of the series' visual effects vendors.<ref name=\"CosaVFX\" />\n\nThere had been considerations for Coulson to return in ''[[Iron Man 3]]'' and ''[[Thor: The Dark World]]'',<ref name=\"CraveOnline\"/> but the character was not slated to appear in any more films.<ref name=\"ComingSoon\"/> Whedon asserts, \"As far as the fiction of the movies, Coulson is dead\",<ref name=\"WhedonFilmsDead\" /> elaborating that \"generally [he feels] like the ''S.H.I.E.L.D.'' audience and ''The Avengers'' audiences are not actually the same group, necessarily,\" and so the films would have to explain Coulson's resurrection again for the film-only audience if he were to be reintroduced.<ref name=\"WhedonDeadElaboration\" /> Gregg reprises the role once again in ''[[Captain Marvel (film)|Captain Marvel]]'' (2019), as the film is set in the 1990s.<ref name=\"CaptainMarvel\" /> Gregg is digitally de-aged by 25 years, along with co-star [[Samuel L. Jackson]], the first time Marvel has done this for an entire film.<ref name=\"Feige/FilmJul2018\" />\n\n===Characterization===\nGregg has stated, \"I think of Agent Coulson, after all these years, as a guy with a full life. I think every day he's somewhere doing something for S.H.I.E.L.D., and yet I don't always know what that is... There's always a different twist. In this one he gets to show more of his wisecracking wit, and in this one he's a little bit more of a badass.\"<ref name=\"shorts\"/> Despite Coulson being called \"the most recognizable face in the Marvel Comics movie universe\", he is depicted as an \"[[everyman]]\" in a universe full of superheroes\u2014\"the glue that binds\" the characters together. Gregg explained his portrayal of the character as \"just a guy grumbling about his job ... he's tasked with handling these kind of diva superheroes, you know? 'Oh, really, Asgard? Dude, just get in the car.'\"<ref name=\"WNBC\"/>\n\n{{quote box|width=33%|align=left|quote=By being so front and center in ''Marvel\u2019s Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.'' in a way that he wasn\u2019t as much in the films ... he\u2019s gotten some power. He\u2019s at the front lines, and what is the cost of that going to be?|source=\u2013Gregg, on how starring in the television series can affect Coulson differently to appearing in the films.<ref name=\"GreggRebuilding\" />}}\nOn whether the resurrected Coulson would be the same as before he died, Gregg said \"I don\u2019t know how you could not change going through what he went through. I think if he hadn\u2019t gone through some kind of change, it wouldn\u2019t be any good. That said, I don\u2019t know if he understands how much he\u2019s changed.\"<ref name=\"GreggScreenRantApr2013\" /> Later exploring some of those changes, Gregg stated \"In some ways, he kinda finds himself not nearly as cold or ruthless as he would like to be, or as he has been. And at the same time, putting together this team, he feels driven by motives inside of himself that he can't quite always make sense of and that feels very new to him.\"<ref name=\"GreggHitFixJan2014\" />\n\nAfter Coulson was promoted to Director of S.H.I.E.L.D., Gregg said \"He kind of got his dream job that I don\u2019t even think he would have ever dreamed he would be given ... he\u2019s got a little bit more of an idealistic, big hearted side of him [than Nick Fury does], some of which is going to be extinguished by the hard decisions he has to make.\" Speaking about the evolving nature of Coulson's relationship with his team, Gregg said \"There\u2019s a way he can afford an intimacy with all of them when they\u2019re part of a small, elite squad on the Bus. It\u2019s different than what\u2019s possible for him as Director of S.H.I.E.L.D.\"<ref name=\"GreggRebuilding\" /> Discussing Coulson's character progression through three seasons in relation to him killing Ward on the alien planet, executive producer [[Jeffrey Bell]] said, \"First season Coulson would have beat Ward up and then thrown him over his shoulder and brought him back to Earth and locked him away. Season two Coulson would have defeated him and left him there on the other planet to fend for himself,\" while season three Coulson paused while the portal to Earth was already closing to take the time to kill Ward.<ref name=\"BellTHRDec2015\" />\n\nFor the fourth season, Coulson is demoted back to field agent status. Gregg said that the reasoning for this \"makes sense given that S.H.I.E.L.D. is coming out of the shadows. There are people that will want their person in charge.\" He felt that Coulson would actually prefer this, saying, \"I always felt like Coulson was happiest in the field. Neither I nor Coulson loved playing and listening while his agents went into dangerous situations. And there are more dramatic possibilities when you have a boss that you have to deal with.\"<ref name=\"GreggSep2016\" />\n\n===Alternate forms===\n====Sarge / Pachakutiq====\nSarge (portrayed by Clark Gregg) is a man who occupies a clone body of Coulson which was created by the powers of the Di'Allas and sent hundred years into the past on his and Izel's home planet.\n\n====Phil Coulson (Chronicom L.M.D.)====\nFollowing the deaths of Izel and Sarge, Enoch and the Chronicoms on his side create a Life Model Decoy of Phil Coulson (portrayed by Clark Gregg) with all of Coulson's memories.\n\n==Reception==\nIn his review for ''Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.''{{'}}s first season, Evan Valentine at Collider named Clark Gregg as one of the high points of the series, noting that the actor was \"one positive I consistently point out in each and every episode\". Valentine stated that \"What made us fall in love with the character from the first ''Iron Man'' to his death in ''The Avengers'' is still alive and kicking. Coulson was able to throw out quips like none other, while also turning on a dime, and expressing serious rage in moments ... Gregg raises the S.H.I.E.L.D. banner high\".<ref name=\"ColliderSeasonReview\" /> Reviewing the episode \"[[The Writing on the Wall (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.)|The Writing on the Wall]]\", which concluded the majority of Coulson's storyline in the series up to that point, Kevin Fitzpatrick of Screen Crush praised how Coulson had become \"unglued\" throughout the series, which had \"pushed the newly-minted director into some dark places\".<ref name=\"Ep2.7ScreenCrush\" /> Eric Goldman, reviewing for [[IGN]], was also positive of the \"unhinged version of Coulson\",<ref name=\"Ep2.7IGN\" /> as well as the more serious leadership role the character took on for the [[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. (season 2)|second season]], with Goldman finding Coulson's decision in \"[[Making Friends and Influencing People]]\" that [[Blizzard (comics)|Donnie Gill]] \"either went with them or had to be taken out\" to be especially notable.<ref name=\"Ep2.3IGN\" />\n\n==Other appearances==\n\n===Animation===\n[[File:Agent Coulson on Ultimate Spider-Man.jpg|thumb|200px|Principal Phil Coulson on ''[[Ultimate Spider-Man (TV series)|Ultimate Spider-Man]]'']]\n* Coulson makes a by-name cameo appearance in the ''[[Iron Man: Armored Adventures]]'' episode \"Extremis\" as one of the S.H.I.E.L.D. agents encountering (and getting knocked down by) the just-mutated renegade agent [[Mallen (comics)|Mallen]].<ref name=\"IronManAAExtremis\" />\n* It was announced at the 2011 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]] that Gregg would return to voice Phil Coulson in the [[cartoon series]] ''[[Ultimate Spider-Man (TV series)|Ultimate Spider-Man]]'', where he appears as a S.H.I.E.L.D. agent and [[Spider-Man|Peter Parker]]'s school [[Head teacher|principal]]. He appears in season 1 and 2.<ref name=\"Toonzone\" /><ref name=\"IGNUltimateSpider\" />\n* He has a brief cameo in the [[anime]] ''[[Marvel Disk Wars: The Avengers]]'' where he is shown in episode 1 of the series showing the S.H.I.E.L.D. facilities include a supervillain prison.\n\n===Comic books===\n[[File:Phil Coulson (Mainstream).jpg|thumb|200px|Phil Coulson in ''Battle Scars'' #6.]]\n* Phil Coulson first appeared in the mainstream [[Marvel Universe]] in [[Christopher Yost]], [[Matt Fraction]] and [[Cullen Bunn]]'s ''[[Battle Scars (comic book)|Battle Scars]]'' #6 (April 2012), in which the character codenamed \"Cheese\" is revealed to be Coulson.<ref name=\"USAToday\"/> Coulson has gone on to appear in other comics set in the mainstream MU, including in the 2013 ''[[Secret Avengers]]'' series by [[Nick Spencer]] and [[Luke Ross]],<ref name=\"SecretAvengers\"/> and in ''[[Thor: God of Thunder]]'' in 2014.<ref name=\"GodofThunderComic\"/>\n** In July 2014 at San Diego Comic-Con International, Marvel Comics announced an ongoing series titled ''S.H.I.E.L.D.'', to be set in the mainstream Marvel Universe, and written by [[Mark Waid]], beginning December 2014. The series is led by Coulson, and sees the canonical introduction of characters that originated from ''Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D'', to which Waid said, \"This is our chance to introduce a lot of the other characters into the Marvel Universe, and give them the Marvel Universe spin.\" Waid described the series as \"done-in-one. Coulson and his team have a mission, and if we need someone for a mission, everyone in the Marvel Universe is available as a potential Agent.\"<ref>{{cite comic | writer=Mark Waid | penciller= Carlos Pacheco | inker= Mariano Taibo, Jason Paz | story= Perfect Bullets | title= S.H.I.E.L.D. | volume= 3 | issue= 1 | date= December 31, 2014 | publisher= Marvel Comics | page= | panel= }}</ref> In this series, Coulson is the Supreme Commander of Special Operations for S.H.I.E.L.D. under Director Maria Hill.\n** He has appeared in ''[[Deadpool]]'', assisting S.H.I.E.L.D. agent Preston and paying Deadpool for his earlier services to S.H.I.E.L.D. During the \"[[Secret Empire (comics)|Secret Empire]]\" event, Coulson learns that Steve Rogers was involved in attracting the Chitauri to invade Earth, and is subsequently shot from the sky and seemingly killed by Deadpool, who was under the order of Rogers.\n** Phil Coulson later turned up alive where he meets with Thunderbolt Ross to talk about the Avengers going global. Coulson states to Ross that he has put together the [[Squadron Supreme|Squadron Supreme of America]] to be the sanctioned superheroes of the United States.<ref>''Avengers'' Vol. 8 #10. Marvel Comics.</ref> The Squadron Supreme of America are revealed to be [[simulacrum]]s created by Mephisto and programmed by the Power Elite so that Phil Coulson can have them be a United States-sponsored superhero team. During the \"[[War of the Realms]]\" storyline, Phil Coulson summons the Squadron Supreme of America to fight the invading Frost Giants. After the Squadron Supreme of America caused the Frost Giants to retreat, Phil Coulson sends them to Ohio which has become a battleground.<ref>''Avengers'' Vol. 8 #18. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n* The comic book continuation of ''[[The Avengers: Earth's Mightiest Heroes]]'' animated television series is told from the perspective of Coulson, despite not appearing as a character in the original show.\n* In 2014, the ''[[Ultimate Marvel|Ultimate]]'' version of Phil Coulson debuted in the ''[[Ultimate Fantastic Four|Ultimate FF]]'' series as an ex Agent of S.H.I.E.L.D. turned Director of the [[Future Foundation]].<ref name=\"newsarama\"/>\n*In November 2015, a 17th-century version of Coulson appeared in the series ''[[Marvel 1602|1602: Witch Hunter Angela]]''.\n*Phil Coulson appears in the ''[[Spidey (comic book)|Spidey]]'' comic book.\n\n===Video games===\n* Phil Coulson appears as a playable character in ''[[Marvel Super Hero Squad Online]]'', voiced by [[Tom Kenny]].\n* Phil Coulson appears as a [[non-player character]] in ''[[Marvel Heroes (video game)|Marvel Heroes]]'' with Clark Gregg reprising his role.\n* Phil Coulson appears as a non-player character in ''[[Marvel: Avengers Alliance]],'' ''Alliance 2,'' and ''Alliance Tactics.''\n* Phil Coulson appears in ''[[Lego Marvel Super Heroes]]'', with Clark Gregg reprising his role. His character becomes playable after the completion of a side mission involving him overseeing Doctor Octopus' community service of fixing the offices of the Daily Bugle. His attack is the \"Destroyer Gun\" he used against Loki in ''The Avengers''.<ref name=\"GameTrailers\"/> He is the most frequent voice on the radio, congratulating the player and makes references to ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]''\n* Phil Coulson is playable in ''[[Marvel: Future Fight]]''. \n* Phil Coulson appears in ''[[Lego Marvel's Avengers]]'', voiced again by Clark Gregg. He gives congratulatory speeches to players over their comms when they complete missions, making references to ''Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.'' (wanting a fish tank and losing a hand) while doing so. \n* Phil Coulson appears as a playable character in ''[[Marvel Avengers Academy]]'', voiced by Billy Kametz.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=xAkh__mww8g|title=Marvel Avengers Academy - Phil Coulson - Billy Kametz VO|via=YouTube|date=August 15, 2017|accessdate=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n* Phil Coulson is a playable character in the match-three mobile game ''[[Marvel Puzzle Quest]]''. He was added to the game in February 2017.<ref name=\"PuzzleQuest\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"MTVThor\">{{cite web |url=http://splashpage.mtv.com/2010/04/28/iron-man-2-thor-clark-gregg/ |title=Clark Gregg's ''Iron Man 2'' S.H.I.E.L.D. Agent Will 'Do Some Exciting Things' In ''Thor'' |author=Blair Marnell |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=April 28, 2010 |accessdate=August 3, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921063114/http://splashpage.mtv.com/2010/04/28/iron-man-2-thor-clark-gregg |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n<!--ref name=\"IGNCameo\">{{cite web |url=https://uk.ign.com/wikis/marvel-studios-cinematic-universe/Teasers_&_Cameos_(Captain_America:_The_First_Avenger) |title=Teasers & Cameos (''Captain America: The First Avenger'') |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728050745/http://www.ign.com/wikis/marvel-studios-cinematic-universe/Teasers_&_Cameos_(Captain_America:_The_First_Avenger) |archivedate=July 28, 2014 |publisher=[[IGN]] }}</ref-->\n\n<ref name=\"Toonzone\">{{cite web|last=Harris |first=Jeffrey |url=http://www.toonzone.net/news/articles/38211/sdcc2011--new-details-and-voice-cast-of-ultimate-spider-man-revealed |title=SDCC2011: New Details and Voice Cast of ''Ultimate Spider-Man'' Revealed |accessdate=August 3, 2011 |publisher=Toon Zone |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822223628/http://www.toonzone.net/news/articles/38211/sdcc2011--new-details-and-voice-cast-of-ultimate-spider-man-revealed |archivedate=August 22, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IGNUltimateSpider\">{{cite web |last=Collura |first=Scott |title=Comic-Con: ''Ultimate Spider-Man'' Toon and ''Avengers'' Season 2 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2011/07/23/comic-con-ultimate-spider-man-toon-and-avengers-season-2 |accessdate=August 3, 2011 |publisher=IGN |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001172710/http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/07/23/comic-con-ultimate-spider-man-toon-and-avengers-season-2 |archivedate=October 1, 2013 |date=July 23, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IronManAAExtremis\">{{cite episode |title=Extremis |series=Iron Man: Armored Adventures |season=2 |number=16 |airdate=March 14, 2012 |network=Nicktoons }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/comics/story/2012-04-25/Agent-Coulson-Avengers-movie-comic-books/54508162/1 |title=Agent Coulson charges into comics with 'Battle Scars' |last=Truitt |first=Brian |work=[[USA Today]] |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=April 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SecretAvengers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=41551 |title=NYCC: Spencer's \"Secret Avengers\" are the Newest Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. |last=Richards |first=Dave |date=October 14, 2012 |publisher=Comic Book Resources|accessdate=October 15, 2012|archivedate=September 27, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927115401/http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=41551 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GodofThunderComic\">\"Thor: God of Thunder\" #19 (April 2014)</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"newsarama\">{{cite web |url=http://www.newsarama.com/20022-fialkov-charts-future-of-marvel-s-ultimate-universe-with-ultimate-ff.html |title=''Ultimate FF'': Fialkov Charts Future of Marvel's Ultimate Universe |publisher=Newsarama.com |date=January 13, 2014 |accessdate=April 7, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114030825/http://www.newsarama.com/20022-fialkov-charts-future-of-marvel-s-ultimate-universe-with-ultimate-ff.html |archivedate=January 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GameTrailers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/jpdqdo/lego-marvel-super-heroes-e3-2013--character-walkthrough--cam- |title=LEGO Marvel Super Heroes Video \u2014 E3 2013: Character Walkthrough (Cam) |publisher=GameTrailers |date=June 12, 2013 |accessdate=August 20, 2013 |archivedate=November 24, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131124005744/http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/jpdqdo/lego-marvel-super-heroes-e3-2013--character-walkthrough--cam- }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CraveOnline\">{{cite web |url=http://www.craveonline.com/film/articles/173736-clark-gregg-on-the-avengers-marvel-one-shots-iron-man-3-and-more |title=Clark Gregg on ''The Avengers'', ''Marvel One-Shots'', ''Iron Man 3'' and more! |last=Bibbiani |first=William |publisher=[[CraveOnline]] |date=September 5, 2011 |accessdate=September 7, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929173225/http://www.craveonline.com/film/articles/173736-clark-gregg-on-the-avengers-marvel-one-shots-iron-man-3-and-more |archivedate=September 29, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ComingSoon\">{{cite news |url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=106835 |title=Agent Coulson Will Not Appear in ''Avengers: Age of Ultron'' |publisher=ComingSoon.net |agency=Associated Press |date=July 23, 2013 |accessdate=September 7, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011213515/http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=106835 |archivedate=October 11, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"shorts\">{{cite web |title=''Marvel One-Shots'': Expanding the Cinematic Universe |url=http://marvel.com/news/story/16398/marvel_one-shots_expanding_the_cinematic_universe |last=Strom |first=Marc |publisher=[[Marvel Comics|Marvel.com]] |date=August 2, 2011 |accessdate=August 3, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"WNBC\">{{cite news |last=Alt |first=Eric |date=September 2, 2011 |