{"title_page": "University of Mary Washington", "text_new": "{{distinguish|University of Mary}}\n{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name         = University of Mary Washington\n| image        = File:George Washington Hall.JPG\n| image_upright = 0.7\n| caption      = George Washington Hall at University of Mary Washington <!--University of Mary Washington [[Seal (device)|Seal]]-->\n| motto        = ''Pro Deo Domo Patria''\n| mottoeng     = For God, home, and country\n| established  = 1908\n| type         = [[Public university|Public]]\n| endowment    = $49.9 million\n| president    = [[Troy Paino]] (since 2016)\n| students     = 4,808<ref name=\"schev.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://research.schev.edu/enrollment/E24_Report.asp|title=E24: Fall Headcount by Tuition Status and Level|website=research.schev.edu}}</ref>\n| undergrad    = 4,398<ref name=\"schev.edu\"/>\n| postgrad     = 410<ref name=\"schev.edu\"/>\n| doctoral     = \n| city         = [[Fredericksburg, Virginia|Fredericksburg]]\n| state        = [[Virginia]]\n| country      = United States\n| campus       = Suburban, 176&nbsp;acres (71.22 [[Hectares|ha]])\n| former_names = {{Plainlist|\n*State Normal and Industrial School for Women at Fredericksburg <small>(1908\u20131938)</small>\n*Mary Washington College <small>(1938\u20131944; 1972\u20132004)</small>\n*Mary Washington College of the University of Virginia <small>(1944\u20131972)</small>}}\n| athletics    = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]] \u2013 [[Capital Athletic Conference|CAC]]\n| nickname     = [[Mary Washington Eagles|Eagles]]\n| mascot       = Eagle\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.umw.edu/}}\n| logo         = University of Mary Washington Logo.png\n| logo_size    = 210px\n| footnotes    = \n|pushpin_map = USA Virginia Northern#USA Virginia#USA\n| coordinates  = {{Coord|38|18|07|N|77|28|30|W|type:edu_scale:2000_region:US-VA|display=inline,title}}\n| staff        = 644\n| faculty      = 386\n| profess      = \n| colors       = Navy Blue and Gray<br />{{color box|navy}}&nbsp;{{color box|gray}}\n| affiliations = [[American Association of State Colleges and Universities|AASCU]]\n[[Council of Public Liberal Arts Colleges|COPLAC]]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Mary Washington''' ('''UMW''') is a public university in [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]]. Founded in 1908 as the '''Fredericksburg Teachers College''', the institution was named '''Mary Washington College''' in 1938 after [[Mary Ball Washington]], mother of the first president of the United States, [[George Washington]]. The General Assembly of Virginia changed the college's name to the University of Mary Washington in 2004 to reflect the addition of graduate and professional programs to the central undergraduate curriculum, as well as the establishment of more than one campus.\n\nEach year, students pursue more than 60 majors and programs of graduate and undergraduate study through the university's three colleges: Arts and Sciences, Business, and Education. One third of UMW's undergraduate students study abroad before graduation, taking advantage of 121 study abroad programs in 56 countries. UMW Athletics' 23 teams compete in the NCAA Division III Capital Athletic Conference. Known as the UMW Eagles, 308 of these student-athletes have been named to All-American teams.\n\n==History==\nOn March 14, 1908, Virginia Governor [[Claude A. Swanson]] signed into law legislation for the establishment of the new State [[Normal school|Normal]] and Industrial School for Women. It was called Fredericksburg Teachers College. The institution was renamed Mary Washington College in 1938 after [[Mary Ball Washington]], mother of the first president of the United States of America, [[George Washington]], and longtime resident of Fredericksburg.<ref>{{cite book\n| last       = Alvey\n| first      = Edward\n| title      = History of Mary Washington College 1908\u20131972\n| publisher  = University of Virginia Press\n| year       = 1974\n| pages      = 227\n| isbn       = 978-0-8139-0528-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| title      = H. Res. 77\n| date       = January 21, 2009\n| publisher  = [[The Library of Congress]]\n| url        = http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&docid=f:hr77ih.txt.pdf\n| accessdate = January 24, 2010}}\n</ref>\n\nIn 1944 the college became associated with the [[University of Virginia]] as its [[Women's colleges in the United States|women's college]]. Until that time, the University of Virginia had not admitted women as undergraduates, except in its education and nursing programs, although its postgraduate programs were coeducational. Following UVA's transition to coeducational status in 1970, the [[Virginia General Assembly]] reorganized Mary Washington College in 1972 as a separate, coeducational institution.<ref>{{cite book\n| last      = Alvey\n| first     = Edward\n| title     = History of Mary Washington College 1908\u20131972\n| publisher = University of Virginia Press\n| year      = 1974\n| pages     = 278, 511\n| isbn      = 978-0-8139-0528-0}}</ref>\n\nThe General Assembly of Virginia enacted legislation changing the college's name to University of Mary Washington on March 19, 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leg1.state.va.us/cgi-bin/legp524.exe?041+ful+CHAP0176|title=Bill Tracking - 2004 session > Legislation|website=leg1.state.va.us}}</ref> to reflect the addition of master's degree programs and the establishment of more than one campus.\n\nThe university's first [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]]-certified building, CGPS North Building, was built in 2007. The university houses stops along the route of the Fredericksburg Regional Transit System (FRED). The school signed an Energy Performance Contact with the [[energy service company]] NORESCO from 2005\u20132007, enabling the campus to install water saving devices which reduced campus water consumption by 50%. NORESCO also installed low energy light fixtures, occupant sensors, HVAC controls, and completed replacement of leaking condensate piping.<ref>{{cite web\n| title      = Water Conservation Measures\n| publisher  = University of Mary Washington\n| url        = http://sustainability.umw.edu/initiatives/water-conservation/\n| accessdate = October 27, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:UMW Trinkle Hall.JPG|thumb|Once the library, Trinkle Hall features a rotunda. Today, it houses the Classics Philosophy and Religion, Mathematics, and Computer Science departments]]\n[[File:UMW Simpson Hall.JPG|thumb|Jepson Hall houses the Science department]]\nThe University of Mary Washington is a public [[liberal arts university]] accredited by the [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]].<ref>{{cite web\n| title      = Institution Details\n| year       = 2009\n| publisher  = [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools Commission on Colleges]]\n| url        = http://www.sacscoc.org/details.asp?instid=46240\n| accessdate = January 23, 2010}}</ref> It is not a [[research university]], but instead focuses on undergraduate education.\n\nMuch of UMW's Fredericksburg campus is located on Marye's Heights, a steep hill which, like Sunken Road (the campus' northeastern boundary), played an important role in the 1862 [[Battle of Fredericksburg]]. The campus is within walking distance to the historic downtown with shops, restaurants and the Rappahannock River.<ref name=\"umw.edu\">{{cite web |url=http://publications.umw.edu/undergraduatecatalog/files/2017/08/Undergrad-Catalog-2017-18_WEB-copy.pdf |title=Undergrad Catalog|website=publications.umw.edu}}</ref> Other campuses are Stafford Campus, seven miles north of Fredericksburg, and Dahlgren Campus, near the [[Naval Surface Warfare Center Dahlgren Division]].\n\nUMW has five pre-professional programs: pre-dental, pre-law, pre-med, pre-pharmacy, and pre-veterinary. Bachelor's degrees include a Bachelor of Science, Bachelor of Arts, and Bachelor of Science in Business Administration in addition to two degree completion programs \u2013 a Bachelor of Science in Nursing (BSN) and a Bachelor of Liberal Studies (BLS).<ref name=\"umw.edu\"/> Master's degrees include a Master of Business Administration (MBA), Master of Education (M.Ed.), Master of Education for Professional Development or Added Endorsement (M.Ed.), Master of Science in Elementary Education (M.S.) and a Master of Geospatial Analysis (MSGA). UMW also offers a Geographic Information Science certificate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://publications.umw.edu/graduatecatalog/files/2017/08/Grad-Catalog-2017-18_WEB-copy.pdf |title= Graduate Catalog|website=publications.umw.edu}}</ref>\n\nFirst-year seminar courses allow students to explore nontraditional topics in nontraditional ways. While topics vary, classes are all capped at 15 students, focus on the development of writing and speaking skills and use active, discussion-based formats. Previous first-year seminars have included \"Beyond the Selfie: Exploring Digital Identities,\" \"Cold Case: Theatre Mysteries,\" \"The Art of Mathematics,\" \"Race & Revolution,\" and \"Science and Technology \u2013 Because We Can, Should We?\"\n\nMany UMW students study abroad before graduation. The university offers 121 approved programs in 56 countries, five exchange programs, and more than 15 programs led by UMW faculty during spring breaks and summer sessions.\n\n==Administration==\nBy statute of the [[Code of Virginia]], the University of Mary Washington is governed by a [[Board of Visitors]], one member of which is elected every two years to serve as [[Rector (academia)|Rector]]. The UMW Board of Visitors is composed of twelve members appointed by the [[Governor of Virginia]] and confirmed by the General Assembly. At least six members of the Board must be alumni of the university, and no more than three may be nonresidents of Virginia. Each member serves a term of four years and may be eligible for reappointment to one successive term.<ref>{{cite web\n| title      = Board of Visitors\n| publisher  = University of Mary Washington\n| url        = http://www.umw.edu/bov/default.php\n| accessdate = January 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Troy Paino]] arrived at UMW July 1, 2016 as its 10th and current President.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umw.edu/news/2016/02/15/umwannouncestenthpresident/|title=UMW Announces Tenth President - News|date=February 15, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Prior to coming to UMW, Paino served for six years as president of [[Truman State University]] in Kirksville, Missouri.\n\n===Past presidents===\n* Edward H. Russell (1908\u20131919)\n* Algernon B. Chandler, Jr. (1919\u20131928)\n* Morgan L. Combs (1929\u20131955)\n* Grellet C. Simpson (1956\u20131974)\n* Prince B. Woodard (1974\u20131982)\n* [[William M. Anderson, Jr.|William M. Anderson, Jr]]. (1983\u20132006)\n* William J. Frawley (2006\u20132007)\n* [[Judy G. Hample]] (2008\u20132010)\n* [[Richard V. Hurley]] (2010\u20132016)\n* [[Troy Paino]] (2016\u2013present)\n\n==Student life==\n'''Honor Convocation''' is held at the start of each academic year. '''Eagle Gathering''' is a candlelit celebration on Ball Circle that marks the start of the year and officially welcomes the newest class to UMW. During '''Family Weekend''', typically held in the fall semester, families visit the campus to get a taste of student life through events, performances and tours. Spirit Week is a series of student events that lead up to Homecoming and the return of UMW alumni to the university for athletic contests and tailgating. '''Senior Countdown''' is an event that celebrates 100 days until graduation for the undergraduate class. '''Spring Formal''' gives students an element of surprise \u2013 students learn the location of the formal (unique each year) only once they're on the buses heading over. '''Mr. UMW''' is a one-of-a-kind talent show in which contestants perform to be named \"Mr. UMW\" by the end of the night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orientation.umw.edu/traditions/|title=Traditions - Undergraduate Orientation|website=orientation.umw.edu}}</ref> WMWC is the school's unlicensed student run [[campus radio]] station.<ref>\"[http://wmwc.umwblogs.org/about-us/ About Us]\", WMWC: UMW Campus Radio. Retrieved March 9, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\nIn 2018, [[Peace Corps]] named UMW was a Top Volunteer-Producing Colleges and Universities for the tenth year in a row, ranking it fourth among small schools. A total of 261 UMW alumni have served in the Peace Corps since the agency's founding in 1961.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umw.edu/news/2018/02/21/umw-named-top-peace-corps-producer-decade/|title=UMW Again Named Top Peace Corps Producer - News|date=February 21, 2018|publisher=}}</ref> UMW became a Peace Corps Prep Program partner in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umw.edu/news/2017/04/03/umw-adopts-peace-corps-prep-program/|title=UMW Adopts Peace Corps Prep Program - News|date=April 3, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nUMW was ranked among the top 382 colleges in the nation by [[The Princeton Review]], which featured UMW in its 2018 issue of \"The Best 382 Colleges.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umw.edu/news/2017/08/01/princeton-review-ranks-umw-among-nations-best-2/|title=Princeton Review Ranks UMW Among Nation's Best - News|date=August 1, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nUMW was unranked nationally for [[US News and World Report]]'s 2018 college rankings, but ranked 17th in the South region.<ref>{{cite web |title=University of Mary Washington {{!}} Mary Washington Overall Rankings {{!}} US News Best Colleges |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/mary-washington-3746/overall-rankings |website=[[US News and World Report]] |accessdate=June 21, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621194017/https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/mary-washington-3746/overall-rankings |archivedate=June 21, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Forbes]] included UMW in its 2018 \"America's Top Colleges,\" ranking the university 276th of 660 undergraduate institutions.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn 2017, the school's debate team was ranked 43rd by the [[Cross Examination Debate Association]].<ref>{{cite web\n| author     = Cross Examination Debate Association\n| title      = CEDA Point Rankings\n| website    = Fullerton.edu\n| publisher  = [[California State University, Fullerton]]\n| url        = http://commweb.fullerton.edu/jbruschke/web/CEDAPoints.aspx\n| accessdate = January 24, 2009}}</ref> In 2009, the team ranked 3rd overall in the [[National Debate Tournament]].<ref>{{cite report\n |title       = National Debate Tournament: Fall 2009 Report\n |first       = Jim\n |last        = Hanson\n |publisher   = Whitman College\n |year        = 2009\n |url         = http://www.whitman.edu/rhetoric/ndt/00-ndtreport-dec-09.doc\n |accessdate  = January 24, 2010\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100603172700/http://www.whitman.edu/rhetoric/ndt/00-ndtreport-dec-09.doc\n |archivedate = June 3, 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nThe university's women's rugby team became champions for Division II in May 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umw.edu/news/2014/05/12/womens-rugby-team-wins-national-championships/|title=Women's Rugby Team Wins National Championship |website=umw.edu | publisher= University of Mary Washington| language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-01}}</ref> UMW's men's rugby team won the USA Rugby's D1AA Fall Championship in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://umweagles.com/sports/mrugby/2017-18/releases/20171203p87y9y|title=UMW Men's Rugby Storms Way to USA Rugby D1AA Fall National Championship; Tops St. Joseph's, 37-13|date=December 3, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2018}}\n\n===Alumni===\n* [[The Dismemberment Plan|Eric Axelson]], musician\n* [[Karen Olsen Beck]], former [[First Ladies and Gentlemen of Costa Rica|First Lady of Costa Rica]]\n* [[Marguerite Bennett]], comic book writer\n* [[Jesse Benton]], conservative political activist and consultant\n* [[Marion Blakey]], former [[Federal Aviation Administration]] Administrator\n* [[Wild Child (band)|Matt Bradshaw]], musician\n* [[Mark Cole (politician)|Mark Cole]], Virginia politician\n* [[Frances D. Cook]], former [[U.S. Ambassador to Burundi]], former [[U.S. Ambassador to Cameroon]], former [[U.S. Ambassador to Oman]]\n* [[Teresa A. H. Djuric]], [[U.S. Air Force]] Brigadier General\n* [[Jean Donovan]], relief worker martyred in [[El Salvador]]\n* [[Elizabeth Edwards]], activist and wife of [[John Edwards]]\n* [[Shin Fujiyama]], co-founder of [[Students Helping Honduras]]\n* [[Barbara Halliday]], Mayor of [[Hayward, California]]\n* [[Carolyn Kreiter-Foronda]], Poet Laureate of Virginia, 2006\u20132008\n* [[Rose M. Likins]], former [[U.S. Ambassador to El Salvador]], former [[U.S. Ambassador to Peru]]\n* [[Mich\u00e8le McQuigg]], Virginia politician\n* [[Judy Muller]], journalist\n* [[Nan Grogan Orrock]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] politician\n* [[Toddy Puller]], Virginia politician\n* [[Judge Reinhold]], actor\n* [[Anne Rudloe]], marine biologist, environmentalist\n* [[Maggie Stiefvater]], writer\n* [[Desiree Marie Velez]], actress\n* [[David Whitaker (politician)|David Whitaker]], [[Arkansas]] politician\n\n===Current, former, and emeritus faculty===\n* [[Bulent Atalay]], [[physicist]] and author\n* [[Julien Binford]], artist\n* [[David Cain (professor)|David Cain]], [[theology|theologian]]\n* [[Claudia Emerson]], poet\n* [[James Farmer]] (1985\u20131998), a leader of the [[Civil Rights Movement]]\n* [[Ron Smith (American poet)|Ron Smith]], poet\n* [[Frank M. Snowden, Jr.]], scholar\n* [[Gregory Stanton]], founder and president of [[Genocide Watch]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Alvey, Edward (1974). ''History of Mary Washington College 1908\u20131972''. University of Virginia Press. {{ISBN|978-0-8139-0528-0}}\n* Crawley, William Bryan (2008). ''University of Mary Washington: A Centennial History, 1908\u20132008''. University of Mary Washington. {{ISBN|978-0-615-21015-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|University of Mary Washington}}\n* [http://www.umw.edu/ Official website]\n* [http://www.umweagles.com/ Official athletics website]\n\n{{Colleges and universities in Virginia}}\n{{Women's Colleges that are Coeducational}}\n{{Council of Public Liberal Arts Colleges}}\n{{Capital Athletic Conference navbox}}\n{{Portal bar|Virginia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mary Washington, University Of}}\n[[Category:Former women's universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:University of Mary Washington| ]]\n[[Category:Public universities]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1908]]\n[[Category:Education in Fredericksburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Fredericksburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Fredericksburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:1908 establishments in Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|University of Mary}}\n{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name         = University of Mary Washington\n| image        = File:George Washington Hall.JPG\n| image_upright = 0.7\n| caption      = George Washington Hall at University of Mary Washington <!--University of Mary Washington [[Seal (device)|Seal]]-->\n| motto        = ''Pro Deo Domo Patria''\n| mottoeng     = For God, home, and country\n| established  = 1908\n| type         = [[Public university|Public]]\n| endowment    = $49.9 million\n| president    = [[Troy Paino]] (since 2016)\n| students     = 4,808<ref name=\"schev.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://research.schev.edu/enrollment/E24_Report.asp|title=E24: Fall Headcount by Tuition Status and Level|website=research.schev.edu}}</ref>\n| undergrad    = 4,398<ref name=\"schev.edu\"/>\n| postgrad     = 410<ref name=\"schev.edu\"/>\n| doctoral     = \n| city         = [[Fredericksburg, Virginia|Fredericksburg]]\n| state        = [[Virginia]]\n| country      = United States\n| campus       = Suburban, 176&nbsp;acres (71.22 [[Hectares|ha]])\n| former_names = {{Plainlist|\n*State Normal and Industrial School for Women at Fredericksburg <small>(1908\u20131938)</small>\n*Mary Washington College <small>(1938\u20131944; 1972\u20132004)</small>\n*Mary Washington College of the University of Virginia <small>(1944\u20131972)</small>}}\n| athletics    = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]] \u2013 [[Capital Athletic Conference|CAC]]\n| nickname     = [[Mary Washington Eagles|Eagles]]\n| mascot       = Eagle\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.umw.edu/}}\n| logo         = University of Mary Washington Logo.png\n| logo_size    = 210px\n| footnotes    = \n|pushpin_map = USA Virginia Northern#USA Virginia#USA\n| coordinates  = {{Coord|38|18|07|N|77|28|30|W|type:edu_scale:2000_region:US-VA|display=inline,title}}\n| staff        = 644\n| faculty      = 386\n| profess      = \n| colors       = Navy Blue and Gray<br />{{color box|navy}}&nbsp;{{color box|gray}}\n| affiliations = [[American Association of State Colleges and Universities|AASCU]]\n[[Council of Public Liberal Arts Colleges|COPLAC]]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Mary Washington''' ('''UMW''') is a public university in [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]]. Founded in 1908 as the '''Fredericksburg Teachers College''', the institution was named '''Mary Washington College''' in 1938 after [[Mary Ball Washington]], mother of the first president of the United States, [[George Washington]]. The General Assembly of Virginia changed the college's name to the University of Mary Washington in 2004 to reflect the addition of graduate and professional programs to the central undergraduate curriculum, as well as the establishment of more than one campus.\n\nEach year, students pursue more than 60 majors and programs of graduate and undergraduate study through the university's three colleges: Arts and Sciences, Business, and Education. One third of UMW's undergraduate students study abroad before graduation, taking advantage of 121 study abroad programs in 56 countries. UMW Athletics' 23 teams compete in the NCAA Division III Capital Athletic Conference. Known as the UMW Eagles, 308 of these student-athletes have been named to All-American teams.\n\n==History==\nOn March 14, 1908, Virginia Governor [[Claude A. Swanson]] signed into law legislation for the establishment of the new State [[Normal school|Normal]] and Industrial School for Women. It was called Fredericksburg Teachers College. The institution was renamed Mary Washington College in 1938 after [[Mary Ball Washington]], mother of the first president of the United States of America, [[George Washington]], and longtime resident of Fredericksburg.<ref>{{cite book\n| last       = Alvey\n| first      = Edward\n| title      = History of Mary Washington College 1908\u20131972\n| publisher  = University of Virginia Press\n| year       = 1974\n| pages      = 227\n| isbn       = 978-0-8139-0528-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| title      = H. Res. 77\n| date       = January 21, 2009\n| publisher  = [[The Library of Congress]]\n| url        = http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&docid=f:hr77ih.txt.pdf\n| accessdate = January 24, 2010}}\n</ref>\n\nIn 1944 the college became associated with the [[University of Virginia]] as its [[Women's colleges in the United States|women's college]]. Until that time, the University of Virginia had not admitted women as undergraduates, except in its education and nursing programs, although its postgraduate programs were coeducational. Following UVA's transition to coeducational status in 1970, the [[Virginia General Assembly]] reorganized Mary Washington College in 1972 as a separate, coeducational institution.<ref>{{cite book\n| last      = Alvey\n| first     = Edward\n| title     = History of Mary Washington College 1908\u20131972\n| publisher = University of Virginia Press\n| year      = 1974\n| pages     = 278, 511\n| isbn      = 978-0-8139-0528-0}}</ref>\n\nThe General Assembly of Virginia enacted legislation changing the college's name to University of Mary Washington on March 19, 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leg1.state.va.us/cgi-bin/legp524.exe?041+ful+CHAP0176|title=Bill Tracking - 2004 session > Legislation|website=leg1.state.va.us}}</ref> to reflect the addition of master's degree programs and the establishment of more than one campus.\n\nThe university's first [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]]-certified building, CGPS North Building, was built in 2007. The university houses stops along the route of the Fredericksburg Regional Transit System (FRED). The school signed an Energy Performance Contact with the [[energy service company]] NORESCO from 2005\u20132007, enabling the campus to install water saving devices which reduced campus water consumption by 50%. NORESCO also installed low energy light fixtures, occupant sensors, HVAC controls, and completed replacement of leaking condensate piping.<ref>{{cite web\n| title      = Water Conservation Measures\n| publisher  = University of Mary Washington\n| url        = http://sustainability.umw.edu/initiatives/water-conservation/\n| accessdate = October 27, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:UMW Trinkle Hall.JPG|thumb|Once the library, Trinkle Hall features a rotunda. Today, it houses the Classics Philosophy and Religion, Mathematics, and Computer Science departments]]\n[[File:UMW Simpson Hall.JPG|thumb|Jepson Hall houses the Science department]]\nThe University of Mary Washington is a public [[liberal arts university]] accredited by the [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]].<ref>{{cite web\n| title      = Institution Details\n| year       = 2009\n| publisher  = [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools Commission on Colleges]]\n| url        = http://www.sacscoc.org/details.asp?instid=46240\n| accessdate = January 23, 2010}}</ref>  It is not a [[research university]], but instead focuses on undergraduate education.\n\nMuch of UMW's Fredericksburg campus is located on Marye's Heights, a steep hill which, like Sunken Road (the campus' northeastern boundary), played an important role in the 1862 [[Battle of Fredericksburg]]. The campus is within walking distance to the historic downtown with shops, restaurants and the Rappahannock River.<ref name=\"umw.edu\">{{cite web |url=http://publications.umw.edu/undergraduatecatalog/files/2017/08/Undergrad-Catalog-2017-18_WEB-copy.pdf |title=Undergrad Catalog|website=publications.umw.edu}}</ref> Other campuses are Stafford Campus, seven miles north of Fredericksburg, and Dahlgren Campus, near the [[Naval Surface Warfare Center Dahlgren Division]].\n\nUMW has five pre-professional programs: pre-dental, pre-law, pre-med, pre-pharmacy, and pre-veterinary. Bachelor's degrees include a Bachelor of Science, Bachelor of Arts, and Bachelor of Science in Business Administration in addition to two degree completion programs \u2013 a Bachelor of Science in Nursing (BSN) and a Bachelor of Liberal Studies (BLS).<ref name=\"umw.edu\"/> Master's degrees include a Master of Business Administration (MBA), Master of Education (M.Ed.), Master of Education for Professional Development or Added Endorsement (M.Ed.), Master of Science in Elementary Education (M.S.) and a Master of Geospatial Analysis (MSGA). UMW also offers a Geographic Information Science certificate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://publications.umw.edu/graduatecatalog/files/2017/08/Grad-Catalog-2017-18_WEB-copy.pdf |title= Graduate Catalog|website=publications.umw.edu}}</ref>\n\nFirst-year seminar courses allow students to explore nontraditional topics in nontraditional ways. While topics vary, classes are all capped at 15 students, focus on the development of writing and speaking skills and use active, discussion-based formats. Previous first-year seminars have included \"Beyond the Selfie: Exploring Digital Identities,\" \"Cold Case: Theatre Mysteries,\" \"The Art of Mathematics,\" \"Race & Revolution,\" and \"Science and Technology \u2013 Because We Can, Should We?\"\n\nMany UMW students study abroad before graduation. The university offers 121 approved programs in 56 countries, five exchange programs, and more than 15 programs led by UMW faculty during spring breaks and summer sessions.\n\n==Administration==\nBy statute of the [[Code of Virginia]], the University of Mary Washington is governed by a [[Board of Visitors]], one member of which is elected every two years to serve as [[Rector (academia)|Rector]]. The UMW Board of Visitors is composed of twelve members appointed by the [[Governor of Virginia]] and confirmed by the General Assembly. At least six members of the Board must be alumni of the university, and no more than three may be nonresidents of Virginia. Each member serves a term of four years and may be eligible for reappointment to one successive term.<ref>{{cite web\n| title      = Board of Visitors\n| publisher  = University of Mary Washington\n| url        = http://www.umw.edu/bov/default.php\n| accessdate = January 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Troy Paino]] arrived at UMW July 1, 2016 as its 10th and current President.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umw.edu/news/2016/02/15/umwannouncestenthpresident/|title=UMW Announces Tenth President - News|date=February 15, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Prior to coming to UMW, Paino served for six years as president of [[Truman State University]] in Kirksville, Missouri.\n\n===Past presidents===\n* Edward H. Russell (1908\u20131919)\n* Algernon B. Chandler, Jr. (1919\u20131928)\n* Morgan L. Combs (1929\u20131955)\n* Grellet C. Simpson (1956\u20131974)\n* Prince B. Woodard (1974\u20131982)\n* [[William M. Anderson, Jr.|William M. Anderson, Jr]]. (1983\u20132006)\n* William J. Frawley (2006\u20132007)\n* [[Judy G. Hample]] (2008\u20132010)\n* [[Richard V. Hurley]] (2010\u20132016)\n* [[Troy Paino]] (2016\u2013present)\n\n==Student life==\n'''Honor Convocation''' is held at the start of each academic year. '''Eagle Gathering''' is a candlelit celebration on Ball Circle that marks the start of the year and officially welcomes the newest class to UMW. During '''Family Weekend''', typically held in the fall semester, families visit the campus to get a taste of student life through events, performances and tours. Spirit Week is a series of student events that lead up to Homecoming and the return of UMW alumni to the university for athletic contests and tailgating. '''Senior Countdown''' is an event that celebrates 100 days until graduation for the undergraduate class. '''Spring Formal''' gives students an element of surprise \u2013 students learn the location of the formal (unique each year) only once they're on the buses heading over. '''Mr. UMW''' is a one-of-a-kind talent show in which contestants perform to be named \"Mr. UMW\" by the end of the night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orientation.umw.edu/traditions/|title=Traditions  -  Undergraduate Orientation|website=orientation.umw.edu}}</ref> WMWC is the school's unlicensed student run [[campus radio]] station.<ref>\"[http://wmwc.umwblogs.org/about-us/ About Us]\", WMWC: UMW Campus Radio. Retrieved March 9, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\nIn 2018, [[Peace Corps]] named UMW was a Top Volunteer-Producing Colleges and Universities for the tenth year in a row, ranking it fourth among small schools. A total of 261 UMW alumni have served in the Peace Corps since the agency's founding in 1961.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umw.edu/news/2018/02/21/umw-named-top-peace-corps-producer-decade/|title=UMW Again Named Top Peace Corps Producer - News|date=February 21, 2018|publisher=}}</ref> UMW became a Peace Corps Prep Program partner in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umw.edu/news/2017/04/03/umw-adopts-peace-corps-prep-program/|title=UMW Adopts Peace Corps Prep Program - News|date=April 3, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nUMW was ranked among the top 382 colleges in the nation by [[The Princeton Review]], which featured UMW in its 2018 issue of \"The Best 382 Colleges.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umw.edu/news/2017/08/01/princeton-review-ranks-umw-among-nations-best-2/|title=Princeton Review Ranks UMW Among Nation's Best - News|date=August 1, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nUMW was unranked nationally for [[US News and World Report]]'s 2018 college rankings, but ranked 17th in the South region.<ref>{{cite web |title=University of Mary Washington {{!}} Mary Washington Overall Rankings {{!}} US News Best Colleges |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/mary-washington-3746/overall-rankings |website=[[US News and World Report]] |accessdate=June 21, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621194017/https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/mary-washington-3746/overall-rankings |archivedate=June 21, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Forbes]] included UMW in its 2018 \"America's Top Colleges,\" ranking the university 276th of 660 undergraduate institutions.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn 2017, the school's debate team was ranked 43rd by the [[Cross Examination Debate Association]].<ref>{{cite web\n| author     = Cross Examination Debate Association\n| title      = CEDA Point Rankings\n| website    = Fullerton.edu\n| publisher  = [[California State University, Fullerton]]\n| url        = http://commweb.fullerton.edu/jbruschke/web/CEDAPoints.aspx\n| accessdate = January 24, 2009}}</ref> In 2009, the team ranked 3rd overall in the [[National Debate Tournament]].<ref>{{cite report\n |title       = National Debate Tournament: Fall 2009 Report\n |first       = Jim\n |last        = Hanson\n |publisher   = Whitman College\n |year        = 2009\n |url         = http://www.whitman.edu/rhetoric/ndt/00-ndtreport-dec-09.doc\n |accessdate  = January 24, 2010\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100603172700/http://www.whitman.edu/rhetoric/ndt/00-ndtreport-dec-09.doc\n |archivedate = June 3, 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nThe university's women's rugby team became  champions for Division II in May 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umw.edu/news/2014/05/12/womens-rugby-team-wins-national-championships/|title=Women's Rugby Team Wins National Championship |website=umw.edu | publisher= University of Mary Washington| language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-01}}</ref> UMW's men's rugby team won the USA Rugby's D1AA Fall Championship in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://umweagles.com/sports/mrugby/2017-18/releases/20171203p87y9y|title=UMW Men's Rugby Storms Way to USA Rugby D1AA Fall National Championship; Tops St. Joseph's, 37-13|date=December 3, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2018}}\n\n===Alumni===\n* [[The Dismemberment Plan|Eric Axelson]], musician\n* [[Karen Olsen Beck]], former [[First Ladies and Gentlemen of Costa Rica|First Lady of Costa Rica]]\n* [[Marguerite Bennett]], comic book writer\n* [[Jesse Benton]], conservative political activist and consultant\n* [[Marion Blakey]], former [[Federal Aviation Administration]] Administrator\n* [[Wild Child (band)|Matt Bradshaw]], musician\n* [[Mark Cole (politician)|Mark Cole]], Virginia politician\n* [[Frances D. Cook]], former [[U.S. Ambassador to Burundi]], former [[U.S. Ambassador to Cameroon]], former [[U.S. Ambassador to Oman]]\n* [[Teresa A. H. Djuric]], [[U.S. Air Force]] Brigadier General\n* [[Jean Donovan]], relief worker martyred in [[El Salvador]]\n* [[Elizabeth Edwards]], activist and wife of [[John Edwards]]\n* [[Shin Fujiyama]], co-founder of [[Students Helping Honduras]]\n* [[Barbara Halliday]], Mayor of [[Hayward, California]]\n* [[Carolyn Kreiter-Foronda]], Poet Laureate of Virginia, 2006\u20132008\n* [[Rose M. Likins]], former [[U.S. Ambassador to El Salvador]], former [[U.S. Ambassador to Peru]] \n* [[Mich\u00e8le McQuigg]], Virginia politician\n* [[Judy Muller]], journalist\n* [[Nan Grogan Orrock]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] politician\n* [[Toddy Puller]], Virginia politician\n* [[Judge Reinhold]], actor\n* [[Anne Rudloe]], marine biologist, environmentalist\n* [[Maggie Stiefvater]], writer\n* [[Desiree Marie Velez]], actress\n* [[David Whitaker (politician)|David Whitaker]], [[Arkansas]] politician\n\n===Current, former, and emeritus faculty===\n* [[Bulent Atalay]], [[physicist]] and author\n* [[Julien Binford]], artist\n* [[David Cain (professor)|David Cain]], [[theology|theologian]]\n* [[Claudia Emerson]], poet\n* [[James Farmer]] (1985\u20131998), a leader of the [[Civil Rights Movement]]\n* [[Ron Smith (American poet)|Ron Smith]], poet\n* [[Frank M. Snowden, Jr.]], scholar\n* [[Gregory Stanton]], founder and president of [[Genocide Watch]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Alvey, Edward (1974). ''History of Mary Washington College 1908\u20131972''. University of Virginia Press. {{ISBN|978-0-8139-0528-0}}\n* Crawley, William Bryan (2008). ''University of Mary Washington: A Centennial History, 1908\u20132008''. University of Mary Washington. {{ISBN|978-0-615-21015-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|University of Mary Washington}}\n* [http://www.umw.edu/ Official website]\n* [http://www.umweagles.com/ Official athletics website]\n\n{{Colleges and universities in Virginia}}\n{{Women's Colleges that are Coeducational}}\n{{Council of Public Liberal Arts Colleges}}\n{{Capital Athletic Conference navbox}}\n{{Portal bar|Virginia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mary Washington, University Of}}\n[[Category:Former women's universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:University of Mary Washington| ]]\n[[Category:Public universities]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1908]]\n[[Category:Education in Fredericksburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Fredericksburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Fredericksburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:1908 establishments in Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Pemilligan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed extra spaces", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Mary_Washington"}
{"title_page": "John J. Pershing", "text_new": "{{short description|Commanding general of the American Expeditionary Force in World War I}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[General of the Armies]]\n| name          = John J. Pershing\n| image         = General John Joseph Pershing head on shoulders.jpg\n| image_size    = 225px\n| caption       = \n| nickname      = \"Black Jack\"<!--Please review the extensive consensus discussion about the nickname in the talk page archives, [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:John_J._Pershing/Archive_2 here] and [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:John_J._Pershing/Archive_3 here], and DO NOT CHANGE the nickname without first presenting NEW INFORMATION to support the change.-->\n| birth_name    = John Joseph Pershing\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1860|9|13|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Laclede, Missouri]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1948|7|15|1860|9|13|mf=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Walter Reed Army Medical Center|Walter Reed General Hospital]]<br />[[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| placeofburial = [[Arlington National Cemetery]], Arlington County, Virginia, U.S.\n| allegiance    = [[United States]]\n| branch        = [[United States Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1886\u20131924\n| rank          = [[General of the Armies]]\n| servicenumber = O-1\n| unit          = \n| commands      = 8th Brigade<ref>Wilson, John B. (1999) [https://books.google.com/books?id=Xv6gxzThIMYC&pg=PA35#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Maneuver and Fire Power: The Evolution of Divisions and Separate Brigades''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113013544/https://books.google.com/books?id=Xv6gxzThIMYC&pg=PA35 |date=January 13, 2018 }} Washington, D.C.: U.S. Government Printing Office. p. 57 {{ISBN|9780160899447}}</ref><ref>Vandiver, v.1 [https://archive.org/details/blackjacklifetim0001vand/page/n619 p. 576] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113013544/https://books.google.com/books?id=5Y6hC0s4URYC&pg=PA576 |date=January 13, 2018 }}</ref><br />[[Mexican Border Service|Mexican Expedition]]<br />[[American Expeditionary Forces|American Expeditionary Force]]<br />[[First United States Army]]<br />[[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]\n| battles       = [[Indian Wars]]\n* [[Apache Wars]]\n* [[Sioux Wars]]\n[[Spanish\u2013American War]]\n* [[Battle of San Juan Hill]]\n[[Philippine\u2013American War]]\n* [[Moro Rebellion]]\n[[Russo-Japanese War]]<br />\n[[Mexican Revolution]]\n* [[Pancho Villa Expedition]]\n[[World War I]]\n* [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]\n| awards        = [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]]<br />[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]]<br />[[Silver Star]]<br />Honorary Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Bath]] (United Kingdom)<br />[[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]] (France)\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = John J Pershing Signature.svg\n| signature_size = 175\n}}\n\n[[General of the Armies]] '''John Joseph''' \"'''Black Jack'''\" '''Pershing''' [[Order of the Bath|GCB]] (September 13, 1860 \u2013 July 15, 1948) was a senior [[United States Army]] [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]]. He served most famously as the commander of the [[American Expeditionary Forces]] (AEF) on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] in [[World War I]], 1917\u201318.\n\nPershing rejected British and French demands that American forces be integrated with their armies, and insisted that the AEF would operate as a single unit under his command, although some American divisions fought under British command, and he also allowed all-black units to be integrated with the [[French army]].\n\nPershing's soldiers first saw serious battle at [[Cantigny, Somme|Cantigny]], [[Battle of Ch\u00e2teau-Thierry (1918)|Chateau-Thierry]], [[Battle of Belleau Wood|Belleau Wood]], and [[Battle of Soissons (1918)|Soissons]]. To speed up the arrival of American troops, they embarked for France leaving heavy equipment behind, and used British and French tanks, artillery, airplanes and other munitions. In September 1918 at [[Battle of Saint-Mihiel|St. Mihiel]], the [[First United States Army|First Army]] was directly under Pershing's command; it overwhelmed the [[Salients, re-entrants and pockets|salient]] \u2013 the encroachment into [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] territory \u2013 that the [[German Army (German Empire)|German Army]] had held for three years. For the [[Meuse-Argonne Offensive]], Pershing shifted roughly 600,000 American soldiers to the heavily defended forests of the Argonne, keeping his divisions engaged in hard fighting for 47 days, alongside the French. The [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] [[Hundred Days Offensive]], which the Argonne fighting was part of, contributed to Germany calling for an [[Armistice of 11 November 1918|armistice]]. Pershing was of the opinion that the war should continue and that all of [[Germany]] should be occupied in an effort to permanently destroy German militarism.\n\nPershing is the only American to be promoted in his own lifetime to [[General of the Armies]] rank, the highest possible rank in the United States Army.<ref group=Notes>An act was passed in 1976 retroactively promoting [[George Washington]] to the same rank but with higher seniority, ensuring that he would always be considered the senior ranking officer in the United States Army.</ref> Allowed to select his own insignia, Pershing chose to use [[General of the Armies#John Pershing|four gold stars]] to distinguish himself from those officers who held the rank of [[General (United States)|General]], which was signified with four silver stars.<ref>{{cite news |date=April 18, 1925 |title=Lest We Forget: Over There; The Reduction of the Marne Salient |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/83256506/ |newspaper=The Evening Star |location=Franklin, IN |page=7 |url-access=subscription  |quote= ... and the boys stood in formation from noon till evening before the arrival of the automobile bearing the impressive insignia of four gold stars. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116131222/https://www.newspapers.com/image/83256506/ |archivedate=January 16, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  After the creation of the five-star [[General of the Army (United States)|General of the Army]] rank during [[World War II]], his rank of General of the Armies could unofficially be considered that of a [[six-star general]], but he died before the proposed insignia could be considered and acted upon by [[United States Congress|Congress]].\n\nSome of his tactics have been criticized both by other commanders at the time and by modern historians. His reliance on costly [[frontal assault]]s, long after other Allied armies had abandoned such tactics, has been blamed for causing unnecessarily high American casualties.<ref>Sheffield, G. (2001). ''Forgotten Victory: The First World War: Myths and Realities'' (2002 ed.). London: Headline Book Publishing. {{ISBN|0-7472-7157-7}}</ref>  In addition to leading the A.E.F. to victory in World War I, Pershing notably served as a mentor to many in the generation of generals who led the United States Army during [[World War II]], including [[George Marshall]], [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], [[Omar Bradley]], [[Lesley J. McNair]], [[George S. Patton]], and [[Douglas MacArthur]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Tucker |first=Spencer C. |date=2014 |title=World War I: The Definitive Encyclopedia and Document Collection |volume=1 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=DBwTBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1238&dq=%22pershing%22+%22macarthur%22+%22mentor%22#v=onepage&q=%22pershing%22%20%22macarthur%22%20%22mentor%22&f=false |location=Santa Barbara, CA |publisher=ABC-CLIO |page=1238 |isbn=978-1-85109-964-1 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430011411/https://books.google.com/books?id=DBwTBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1238&dq=%22pershing%22+%22macarthur%22+%22mentor%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjI7I-rpbzLAhXIdR4KHVtsCgcQ6AEIIjAB#v=onepage&q=%22pershing%22%20%22macarthur%22%20%22mentor%22&f=false |archivedate=April 30, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Keane |first=Michael |date=2012 |title=George S. Patton: Blood, Guts, and Prayer |url=https://books.google.com/?id=byMjBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA73&dq=%22pershing%22+%22patton%22+%22mentor%22#v=onepage&q=%22pershing%22%20%22patton%22%20%22mentor%22&f=false |location=Washington, DC |publisher=Regnery History |page=73 |isbn=978-1-59698-326-7 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430082127/https://books.google.com/books?id=byMjBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA73&dq=%22pershing%22+%22patton%22+%22mentor%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjhxqjpprzLAhXCRSYKHd_pDaYQ6AEIJTAA#v=onepage&q=%22pershing%22%20%22patton%22%20%22mentor%22&f=false |archivedate=April 30, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPershing was born on a farm near [[Laclede, Missouri]], to businessman John Fletcher Pershing and homemaker Ann Elizabeth Thompson. Pershing's great-great-grandfather, Frederick Pershing, whose name originally was Pfersching, [[Alsatians (people)|emigrated from Alsace]], leaving [[Amsterdam]] on the ship ''Jacob'', and arriving in [[Philadelphia]] on October 2, 1749. Pershing's mother was of [[English American|English descent]]. He also had five siblings: brothers James F. (1862\u20131933) and  Ward (1874\u20131909), and sisters Mary Elizabeth (1864\u20131928), Anna May (1867\u20131955) and Grace (1867\u20131903); three other children died in infancy.<ref>Ruth and Rose, twins who died in 1872, and Frederick, who died in 1876. Vandiver, v. 1, p. 6</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Associated Press |title=Pershing's Sister Dies at 89 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9C01E6D9103AE53BBC4C53DFBE66838E649EDE |quote=Anna May Pershing, a sister of the late General of the Armies John J. Pershing, died yesterday at the age of 89. ... |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 4, 1955 |accessdate=2015-02-06 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207003237/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9C01E6D9103AE53BBC4C53DFBE66838E649EDE |archivedate=February 7, 2015 |df=mdy-all |author-link=Associated Press }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Staff |title=James F. Pershing Dies At Age Of 71 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=990DEEDC1E3AE333A25753C1A9649C946294D6CF |quote=Brother of General Succumbs to Cerebral Thrombosis After a Long Illness. Was President of an Insurance Company. Formerly a Clothing Manufacturer. ... |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 10, 1933 |accessdate=2015-02-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207053605/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=990DEEDC1E3AE333A25753C1A9649C946294D6CF |archivedate=February 7, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> When the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] began, his father supported the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] and was a [[sutler]] for the [[18th Missouri Volunteer Infantry]].\n\nPershing attended a school in Laclede that was reserved for precocious students who were also the children of prominent citizens.  Completing high school in 1878, he became a teacher of local [[African American]] children.  While pursuing his teaching career, Pershing also studied at the State [[Normal School]] (now [[Truman State University]]) in [[Kirksville, Missouri]], from which he graduated in 1880 with a [[bachelor of science]] degree in [[Didactic method|scientific didactics]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Russell |first=Thomas Herbert |date=1919 |title=America's War for Humanity: Pictorial History of the World War for Liberty |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CVs-AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA497 |location=New York, NY |publisher=L.H. Walter |page=497 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113013544/https://books.google.com/books?id=CVs-AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA497 |archivedate=January 13, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Muench |first1=James |last2=Miller |first2=John E. |date=2006 |title=Five Stars: Missouri's Most Famous Generals |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rCkzoxphG80C&pg=PA82 |location=Columbia, MO |publisher=University of Missouri Press |page=82 |isbn=978-0-8262-1656-4 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113013544/https://books.google.com/books?id=rCkzoxphG80C&pg=PA82 |archivedate=January 13, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Two years later, he applied to the [[United States Military Academy]]. Pershing later admitted that serving in the military was secondary to attending West Point, and he had applied because the education offered was much better than that obtainable in rural Missouri.\n\n==West Point years==\n[[File:CadetJPershing.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Pershing as a cadet in 1886]]\n\nPershing was sworn in as a West Point cadet in the fall of 1882.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lacey |first=Jim |date=2008 |title=Pershing: Lessons in Leadership |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FFCAHW7vcWkC&pg=PA10 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |page=10 |isbn=978-0-230-61445-1 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113013544/https://books.google.com/books?id=FFCAHW7vcWkC&pg=PA10 |archivedate=January 13, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  He was selected early for leadership positions and became successively First Corporal, First Sergeant, First Lieutenant, and First Captain, the highest possible cadet rank.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=MacAdam |first=George |date=December 1, 1918 |title=The Life of General Pershing: West Point Days |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O6Q6AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA161 |magazine=The World's Work |location=Garden City, NY |publisher=Doubleday, Page & Company |page=161 |ref={{sfnRef|\"The Life of General Pershing: West Point Days\"}} |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113013544/https://books.google.com/books?id=O6Q6AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA161 |archivedate=January 13, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Pershing also commanded, ''[[ex officio]],'' the honor guard that saluted the funeral train of [[President of the United States|President]] [[Ulysses S. Grant]] as it passed West Point in August 1885.<ref>{{cite book |last=Flood |first=Charles Bracelen |date=2011 |title=Grant's Final Victory: Ulysses S. Grant's Heroic Last Year |url=https://archive.org/details/grantsfinalvicto0000floo |url-access=registration |location=Philadelphia, PA |publisher=Da Capo Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/grantsfinalvicto0000floo/page/241 241] |isbn=978-0-306-82151-6}}</ref>\n\nPershing graduated in the summer of 1886 ranked 30th in his class of 77, and was commissioned a [[Second Lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]];<ref>{{cite book |last=Henry |first=Mark |date= 2012-08-20|title=The US Army of World War I |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v90bDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA10 |location=Cumnor Hill, Oxford, UK |publisher=Osprey Publishing |page=10 |isbn=978-1-84176-486-3 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113013544/https://books.google.com/books?id=v90bDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA10 |archivedate=January 13, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> he was commended by the West Point Superintendent, General [[Wesley Merritt]], who said Pershing gave early promise of becoming an outstanding officer.<ref>{{cite magazine |date=October 1, 1918 |title=General Pershing |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1fZYAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA10-PA5 |magazine=The American Marine Engineer |volume=XIII |issue=10 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=National Marine Engineers' Beneficial Association |page=5 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113013544/https://books.google.com/books?id=1fZYAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA10-PA5 |archivedate=January 13, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  Pershing briefly considered petitioning the Army to let him study law and delay the start of his mandatory military service.<ref>{{cite book |last=Marley |first=David |date=2008 |title=Wars of the Americas: A Chronology of Armed Conflict in the Western Hemisphere, 1492 to the Present |url=https://books.google.com/?id=An4ZAQAAIAAJ&dq=pershing+take+leave+%22study+law%22&q=%22taking+leave+to+study+law%22 |location=Santa Barbara, CA |publisher=ABC-CLIO |page=961 |isbn=978-0-87436-837-6 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113013544/https://books.google.com/books?id=An4ZAQAAIAAJ&dq=pershing+take+leave+%22study+law%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22taking+leave+to+study+law%22 |archivedate=January 13, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  He also considered joining several classmates in a partnership that would pursue development of an irrigation project in [[Oregon]].{{sfn|\"The Life of General Pershing: West Point Days\"|page=172}}  He ultimately decided against both courses of action in favor of active Army duty.<ref>{{cite book |last=Worcester Hall Rowell |first=Cora |date=1920 |title=Leaders of the Great War |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9k4ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA261 |location=New York, NY |publisher=The Macmillan Company |page=261}}</rerf>\n\n==Early career==\nPershing reported for active duty on September 30, 1886, and was assigned to Troop L of the [[6th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|6th U.S. Cavalry]] stationed at [[Fort Bayard National Cemetery|Fort Bayard]], in the [[New Mexico Territory]]. While serving in the 6th Cavalry, Pershing participated in several [[American Indian Wars|Indian campaigns]] and was cited for bravery for actions against the [[Apache]]. During his time at [[Fort Stanton]], Pershing and close friends Lt. [[Julius A. Penn]] and Lt. [[Richard B. Paddock]] were nicknamed \"The Three Green P's,\" spending their leisure time hunting and attending Hispanic dances. Pershing's sister Grace married Paddock in 1890.<ref name=vandiver1>Vandiver, v.1, p. 67.</ref>\n\nBetween 1887 and 1890, Pershing served with the 6th Cavalry at various postings in [[California]], [[Arizona]], and [[North Dakota]]. He also became an expert marksman and, in 1891, was rated second in pistol and fifth in rifle out of all soldiers in the U.S. Army.\n\nOn December 9, 1890, Pershing and the 6th Cavalry arrived at [[Sioux City, Iowa]], where Pershing played a role in suppressing the last uprisings of the [[Sioux|Lakota (Sioux)]] [[Native Americans in the United States|Indians]]. Though he and his unit did not participate in the [[Wounded Knee Massacre]], they did fight three days after it on January 1, 1891 when Sioux warriors attacked the 6th Cavalry's supply wagons. When the Sioux began firing at the wagons, Pershing and his troops heard the shots, and rode more than six miles to the location of the attack. The cavalry fired at the forces of Chief War Eagle, causing them to retreat. This would be the only occasion where Pershing would see action in the [[Ghost Dance War|Ghost Dance campaign]].<ref name=\"WK\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JccTct3j3DUC&pg=PA39&dq=John+J.+Pershing+wounded+knee#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=John J. Pershing|author=McNeese, Tim|page=39|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing]]|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7910-7404-6|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506112925/https://books.google.com/books?id=JccTct3j3DUC&pg=PA39&dq=John+J.+Pershing+wounded+knee&hl=en&ei=7OfNTrS-KarW0QGD3ungBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|archivedate=May 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1891 he was assigned as the Professor of Military Science and Tactics at the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln]], a position he held until 1895. While carrying out this assignment, Pershing attended the university's [[University of Nebraska College of Law|College of Law]],<ref>{{cite magazine |last=MacAdam |first=George |date=March 1, 1919 |title=The Life of General Pershing |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r0RYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA543 |magazine=The World's Work |location=Garden City, NY |publisher=Doubleday, Page & Company |page=543 }}</ref> from which he received his [[bachelor of laws|LL.B.]] degree in 1893.<ref>{{cite magazine |date=April 1, 1920 |title=Alumni in the Primaries |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VeDmAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA6 |magazine=The University Journal |location=Lincoln, NE |publisher=University of Nebraska |page=6}}</ref> He formed a drill company of chosen university cadets, Company A.  In March 1892, it won the Maiden Prize competition of the National Competitive Drills in [[Omaha, Nebraska]]. The Citizens of Omaha presented the company with a large silver cup, the \"Omaha Cup.\" On October 2, 1894, former members of Company A established a fraternal military drill organization named the Varsity Rifles. The group renamed itself the [[Pershing Rifles]] in 1895 in honor of its mentor and patron.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gen. John J. Pershing: Contributions and Commemoration at UNL 1891-1895: Pershing Rifles|url=http://unlhistory.unl.edu/exhibits/show/generalpershing/the-pershing-rifles/pershingrifles|website=Nebraska U: A Collaborative History|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031104/http://unlhistory.unl.edu/exhibits/show/generalpershing/the-pershing-rifles/pershingrifles|archivedate=December 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Pershing maintained a close relationship with Pershing Rifles for the remainder of his life.<ref>{{cite book |last=O'Connor |first=Richard |date=1961 |title=Black Pershing Company |url=https://archive.org/stream/blackjackpershin030769mbp#page/n75/mode/2up/ |location=Garden City, NY |publisher=Doubleday & Company |page=73}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Christy |first=Helen Anne Hirst |date=1996 |title=Hirst/Sheppard family history |url=https://books.google.com/?id=IZ1RAAAAMAAJ&q=%22pershing+rifles%22+troops+review+pershing+1933&dq=%22pershing+rifles%22+troops+review+pershing+1933 |location=Denver, CO |publisher=H. A. H. Christy |page=11}}</ref>\n\nOn October 20, 1892,<ref>{{cite web|last=US Army Center for Military History|title=John Joseph Pershing|url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/faq/pershing.html|work=US Army Chiefs of Staff|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507013003/http://www.history.army.mil/html/faq/pershing.html|archivedate=May 7, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Pershing was promoted to [[US First Lieutenant|first lieutenant]] and in 1895 took command of a troop of the [[10th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|10th Cavalry Regiment]], one of the original [[Buffalo Soldier]] regiments composed of African-American soldiers under white officers. From [[Fort Assinniboine]] in north central [[Montana]], he commanded an expedition to the south and southwest that rounded up and deported a large number of [[Cree Indians]] to [[Canada]].\n\n==West Point instructor {{anchor|nickname}}==\n[[File:CAPTJPershing.jpg|thumb|187px|Captain John J. Pershing, c.1902]]\n[[File:John J. Pershing and family.jpg|right|thumb|187px|Pershing with his wife Helen and three of their children]]\n\nIn 1897, Pershing was appointed to the West Point tactical staff as an instructor, where he was assigned to Cadet Company A. Because of his strictness and rigidity, Pershing was unpopular with the cadets, who took to calling him <!--SEE NOTE-->\"[[Nigger]] Jack\"<!--NOTE: *Extensive* discussions about Pershing's nickname can be found in the archives, especially http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:John_J._Pershing/Archive_2 and http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:John_J._Pershing/Archive_3.  Please do not change the nickname in the article without first reading that discussion, then presenting '''''new''''' information not previusly considered, in order to get a consensus for your proposed change.  Changes made without consensus will most probably be reverted.--> because of his service with the 10th Cavalry.<ref name=vand171>Vandiver v.1, p.171</ref><ref>[http://www.nps.gov/pwso/honor/pershing.htm \"Buffalo Soldier Cavalry Commander\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070915020632/http://www.nps.gov/pwso/honor/pershing.htm |date=September 15, 2007 }} on the [[National Park Service]] website</ref><ref>Bak, Richard, Editor. \"The Rough Riders\" by Theodore Roosevelt. p. 172. Taylor Publishing, 1997.</ref>\n\nDuring the course of his tour at the [[United States Military Academy|Academy]], this epithet softened to \"Black Jack,\" although, according to Vandiver, \"the intent remained hostile.\"<ref name=vand171 /> Still, this nickname would stick with Pershing for the rest of his life, and was known to the public as early as 1917.<ref name=moros>{{cite news |author=Staff |title=Pershing Won Fame in Moros Campaign ... 'Black Jack' Was Youngest West Pointer Ever Made General in Peacetime |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1917/05/19/102345143.pdf |quote=Maj. Gen. John J. Pershing, the famous \"Black jack\" of the regulars, will go down in history as the first American army officer to command troops on the battlefields of Europe. He (Pershing) is one of the officers picked by Colonel Roosevelt, when the Colonel was President, for rapid promotion to the highest of army commands. ... |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 19, 1917 |accessdate=2015-02-06 }}</ref>\n\n==Spanish\u2013 and Philippine\u2013American wars==\nAt the start of the [[Spanish\u2013American War]], First Lieutenant Pershing was the regimental quartermaster for the 10th Cavalry; he fought on Kettle and [[Battle of San Juan Hill|San Juan Hill]]s in [[Cuba]], and was cited for gallantry. In 1919, he was awarded the [[Citation Star|Silver Citation Star]] for these actions, and in 1932 the award was upgraded to the [[Silver Star]] decoration. A commanding officer here commented on Pershing's calm demeanor under fire, saying he was \"cool as a bowl of cracked ice.\".<ref name=boot>Boot, p. 191</ref>  Pershing also served with the 10th Cavalry during the siege and surrender of [[Santiago de Cuba]].\n\nPershing was commissioned as a major of United States Volunteers on August 26, 1898, and assigned as an ordnance officer.  In March 1899, after suffering from [[malaria]], Pershing was put in charge of the Office of Customs and Insular Affairs which oversaw occupation forces in territories gained in the Spanish\u2013American War, including Cuba, [[Puerto Rico]], the [[Philippines]], and [[Guam]]. <!--In the Philippines, he would be partly responsible for \"inflicting thousands of civilian casualties\"<ref name=\"http://www.law.umaryland.edu/marshall/crsreports/crsdocuments/rl31672_11182003.pdf\">CRS Report for Congress: Terrorism in Southeast Asia Updated November 18, 2003. Retrieved Nov 29, 2010. http://academics.utep.edu/Portals/1719/Publications/Pershing.pdf</ref> during the extensive combat operations against Filipino Muslims in Jolo.--> He was honorably discharged from the volunteers and reverted to his permanent rank of first lieutenant on May 12, 1899.  He was again commissioned as a major of Volunteers on June 6, 1899, this time as an assistant adjutant general.\n\nWhen the [[Philippine\u2013American War]] began, Pershing reported to Manila on August 17, 1899, was assigned to the Department of [[Mindanao]] and [[Jolo]], and commanded efforts to suppress the [[Filipino Insurrection]].<ref name=Rojas>{{cite web|last=Rojas|first=Julietta|title=John J. Pershing: A Teacher's Guide|url=http://academics.utep.edu/Portals/1719/Publications/Pershing.pdf|accessdate=April 12, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017030751/http://academics.utep.edu/Portals/1719/Publications/Pershing.pdf|archivedate=October 17, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On November 27, 1900, Pershing was appointed Adjutant General of his department and served in this posting until March 1, 1901. He was cited for bravery for actions on the [[Cagayan River (Mindanao)|Cagayan River]] while attempting to destroy a Philippine stronghold at Macajambo.\n\nPershing wrote in his autobiography that \"The bodies [of some [[Moro people|Moro]] outlaws] were publicly buried in the same grave with a dead pig.\"<ref name=autobio /><ref>{{Cite web|author=Johnson, Jenna and DelReal, Jose A.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/02/20/trumps-story-about-killing-terrorists-with-bullets-dipped-in-pigs-blood-is-likely-not-true/|title=Trump tells story about killing terrorists with bullets dipped in pigs' blood, though there's no proof of it|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=February 20, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160228092733/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/02/20/trumps-story-about-killing-terrorists-with-bullets-dipped-in-pigs-blood-is-likely-not-true/|archivedate=February 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> This treatment was used against captured ''[[juramentado]]'' so that the superstitious Moro would believe they would be going to hell.<ref>Smythe, Donald (1973) [https://archive.org/details/guerrillawarrior00dona <!--  quote=pig. --> ''Guerrilla Warrior: The Early Life of John J. Pershing''], p.162 New York: Scribner. {{isbn|0684129337}}. Quote: \"To combat the ''jurementado'', Pershing tried burying him when caught with a pig, thinking that this was equivalent to burying the Moro in hell, for pigs were impure animals to a Moslem.\"</ref> Pershing added that \"it was not pleasant [for the Army] to have to take such measures\".<ref name=autobio>Pershing, John (2013) [https://books.google.com/books?id=a74_JIbehzsC&q=materially+reduced+#v=snippet&q=materially%20reduced&f=false ''My Life Before the World War, 1860\u20131917: A Memoir''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430233418/https://books.google.com/books?id=a74_JIbehzsC |date=April 30, 2016}}, pp. 284-85 Lexington, Kentucky: [[University Press of Kentucky]]. {{isbn|9780813141978}} Quote: \"... the commanding office, Colonel Frank West, had seen the attack and called out the guard, and before the man could kill anyone else he was shot dead in his tracks. These ''juramentado'' attacks were materially reduced in number by a practice the army had already adopted, one that Muhhamadans held in abhorrence. The bodies were publicly buried in the same grave with a dead pig. It was not pleasant to have to take such measures, but the prospect of going to hell instead of heaven sometimes deterred the would-be assassins.\" A footnote in the 2013 edition cites a letter from Maj. Gen. J. Franklin Bell to Pershing: \"Of course there is nothing to be done, but I understand it has long been a custom to bury (insurgents) with pigs when they kill Americans. I think this a good plan, for if anything will discourage the (insurgents) it is the prospect of going to hell instead of to heaven. You can rely on me to stand by you in maintaining this custom. It is the only possible thing we can do to discourage crazy fanatics.\"</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Lacey, Jim |title=Pershing (Great Generals) |date=2008 |publisher=PalgraveMacmillan |isbn=978-0-230-60383-7 |page=66 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=FFCAHW7vcWkC&pg=PP6&dq=lacey+pershing}}</ref> Historians do not believe that Pershing was directly involved with such incidents, or that he personally gave such orders to his subordinates. Letters and memoirs from soldiers describing events similar to this do not have credible evidence of Pershing having been personally involved.<ref name=wapohorton /><ref name=nytqiu /> Similarly, the claim made by [[Donald Trump]] during his presidential campaign in February 2016 that Pershing executed 49 \"Muslim terrorists\" with bullets dipped in pig's blood, then let the 50th go free to spread the word about the religious atrocity, which Trump alluded to again while serving as president in August 2017, has been repeatedly debunked by historians, who find no evidence that such an incident occurred.<ref name=wapohorton>Horton, Alex (August 18, 2017) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/08/18/after-barcelona-attack-trump-said-to-study-general-pershing-heres-what-the-president-got-wrong/ \"Trump said to study General Pershing. Here's what the president got wrong\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819024443/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/08/18/after-barcelona-attack-trump-said-to-study-general-pershing-heres-what-the-president-got-wrong/ |date=August 19, 2017}} ''[[The Washington Post]]''</ref><ref name=nytqiu>Qiu, Linda (August 18, 2017) [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/17/us/politics/trump-tweet-pershing-fact-check.html?_r=0 \"Study Pershing, Trump Said. But the Story Doesn't Add Up\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819022903/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/17/us/politics/trump-tweet-pershing-fact-check.html?_r=0 |date=August 19, 2017}} ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref><ref>Mikkelson, David (August 17, 2017) [http://www.snopes.com/rumors/pershing.asp \"Fact Check: General Pershing on How to Stop Islamic Terrorists\"] [[Snopes.com]]</ref><ref group=Notes>On August 17, 2017 Trump tweeted: \"Study what General Pershing of the United States did to terrorists when caught. There was no more Radical Islamic Terror for 35 years!\"</ref>\n\nOn June 30, 1901, Pershing was honorably discharged from the Volunteers and he reverted to the rank of captain in the [[Regular Army (United States)|Regular Army]] to which he had been promoted on February 2, 1901. He served with the [[1st Cavalry Regiment (United States)|1st Cavalry Regiment]] in the Philippines. He later was assigned to the [[15th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|15th Cavalry Regiment]], serving as an intelligence officer and participating in actions [[Moro Rebellion|against the Moros]]. He was cited for bravery at [[Lake Lanao]]. In June 1901, he served as Commander of Camp Vicars in Lanao, Philippines, after the previous camp commander had been promoted to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]].\n\n==Rise to general==\nIn June 1903, Pershing was ordered to return to the United States. President [[Theodore Roosevelt]], taken by Pershing's ability, petitioned the Army General Staff to promote Pershing to [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]]. At the time, Army officer promotions were based primarily on seniority rather than merit,<ref name=boot /> and although there was widespread acknowledgment that Pershing should serve as a colonel, the Army General Staff declined to change their seniority-based promotion tradition just to accommodate Pershing. They would not consider a promotion to [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] or even [[Major (United States)|major]]. This angered Roosevelt, but since the President could only name and promote army officers in the General ranks, his options for recognizing Pershing through promotion were limited.\n\n[[File:Leon Hornecker-general-Pershing.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Portrait of Captain Pershing by [[L\u00e9on Hornecker]] (1903)]]\n\nIn 1904, Pershing was assigned as the Assistant Chief of Staff of the Southwest Army Division stationed at [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]]. In October 1904, he attended the [[United States Army War College|Army War College]], and then was ordered to [[Washington, D.C.]] for \"general duties unassigned.\"\n\nSince Roosevelt could not yet promote Pershing, he petitioned the [[United States Congress]] to authorize a diplomatic posting, and Pershing was stationed as [[military attach\u00e9]] in [[Tokyo]] in 1905. Also in 1905, Pershing married Helen Frances Warren, the daughter of powerful [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] [[Francis E. Warren]], a [[Wyoming]] [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] who served at different times as chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services|Military Affairs]] and [[United States Senate Committee on Appropriations|Appropriations]] Committees. This union with the daughter of a powerful politician who had also received the [[Medal of Honor]] during the [[American Civil War]] continued to aid Pershing's career even after his wife died in 1915.<ref name=\"arlington\">{{cite web |url=http://www.warren.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=4696 |title=F. E. Warren History |work=Factsheets |publisher=U.S. Air Force \u2013 Warren AFB |accessdate=January 18, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090905010958/http://www.warren.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=4696 |archivedate=September 5, 2009 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter serving as an [[Military attach\u00e9s and observers in the Russo-Japanese War|observer in the Russo-Japanese War]] attached to General [[Kuroki Tamemoto]]'s [[First Army (Japan)|Japanese First Army]] in [[Manchuria]] from March to September,<ref>{{cite book |last=Kowner |first=Rotem |authorlink=Rotem Kowner |year=2006 |title=Historical Dictionary of the Russo-Japanese War |publisher=The Scarecrow Press |location= |isbn=978-0-8108-4927-3 |page=282}}</ref> Pershing returned to the United States in the fall of 1905.  President Roosevelt employed his presidential prerogative and nominated Pershing as a [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]], a move which Congress approved. In skipping three ranks and more than 835 officers senior to him, the promotion gave rise to accusations that Pershing's appointment was the result of political connections and not military abilities.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lacey |first=Jim |date=2008 |title=Pershing: A Biography: lessons in Leadership |url=https://books.google.com/?id=FFCAHW7vcWkC&pg=PA55&lpg=PA55&dq=pershing+political+promotion#v=onepage&q=pershing%20political%20promotion&f=false |location=New York, NY |publisher=Palgrave MacMillan |page=55 |isbn=978-0-230-61445-1 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430063554/https://books.google.com/books?id=FFCAHW7vcWkC&pg=PA55&lpg=PA55&dq=pershing+political+promotion&source=bl&ots=cDaGuPPP5k&sig=OUoOu433nY3EVtE3kak309CaZeQ&hl=en&ei=d-ogTa2ZO4essAOCnJy5Ag&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&sqi=2&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=pershing%20political%20promotion&f=false |archivedate=April 30, 2016 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, several other junior officers were similarly advanced to brigadier general ahead of their peers and seniors, including [[Albert Leopold Mills|Albert L. Mills]] (captain), [[Tasker H. Bliss]] (major), and [[Leonard Wood]] (captain). Pershing's promotion, while unusual, was not unprecedented, and had the support of many soldiers who admired his abilities.<ref>{{cite book |last=Runkle |first=Benjamin |date=2011 |title=Wanted Dead or Alive: Manhunts from Geronimo to Bin Laden |url=https://archive.org/details/wanteddeadoraliv0000runk |url-access=registration |quote=john j. pershing promotion brigadier seniority. |location=New York, NY |publisher=Palgrave MacMillan |pages=[https://archive.org/details/wanteddeadoraliv0000runk/page/77 77]\u201379 |isbn=978-0-230-10485-3 |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Goldhurst |first=Richard |date=1977 |title=Pipe Clay and Drill: John J. Pershing, the Classic American Soldier |url=https://books.google.com/?id=rGorAQAAIAAJ&q=%22john+j.+pershing%22+%22medal+of+honor%22+%22bagsak%22&dq=%22john+j.+pershing%22+%22medal+of+honor%22+%22bagsak%22 |location=Pleasantville, NY |publisher=Reader's Digest Press |page=151 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602161510/https://books.google.com/books?id=rGorAQAAIAAJ&q=%22john+j.+pershing%22+%22medal+of+honor%22+%22bagsak%22&dq=%22john+j.+pershing%22+%22medal+of+honor%22+%22bagsak%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=gtDwVNWUC4W_ggTP8IKQDw&ved=0CBwQ6AEwADgK |archivedate=June 2, 2015 |df=mdy-all |isbn=9780883490976}}</ref>\n\nIn 1908, Pershing briefly served as a U.S. military observer in the [[Balkans]], an assignment which was based in [[Paris]]. Upon returning to the United States at the end of 1909, Pershing was assigned once again to the Philippines, an assignment in which he served until 1913. While in the Philippines, he served as Commander of [[Fort William McKinley|Fort McKinley]], near Manila, and also was the governor of the Moro Province. The last of Pershing's four children was born in the Philippines, and during this time he became an [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]].\n\nIn 1913, Pershing was recommended for the [[Medal of Honor]] following his actions at the [[Battle of Bud Bagsak]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Arnold |first=James R. |date=2011 |title=The Moro War: How America Battled a Muslim Insurgency in the Philippine Jungle, 1902\u20131913 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=S1Q5OYAPccoC&pg=PA240&dq=%22pershing%22+%22medal+of+honor%22+%22bagsak%22#v=onepage&q=%22pershing%22%20%22medal%20of%20honor%22%20%22bagsak%22&f=false |location=New York, NY |publisher=Bloomsbury Press |page=240 |isbn=978-1-60819-024-9 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125040155/https://books.google.com/books?id=S1Q5OYAPccoC&pg=PA240&dq=%22pershing%22+%22medal+of+honor%22+%22bagsak%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zYU6VdjsIMOHNp7BgKAC&ved=0CDkQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=%22pershing%22%20%22medal%20of%20honor%22%20%22bagsak%22&f=false |archivedate=November 25, 2015 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> He wrote to the [[List of Adjutants General of the U.S. Army|Adjutant General]] to request that the recommendation not be acted on, though the board which considered the recommendation had already voted no before receiving Pershing's letter.<ref>{{cite book |last=MacAdam |first=George |date=1919 |title=The Life of General Pershing: The World's Work, Volume 38 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=6uRAAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA103&dq=%22pershing%22+%22medal+of+honor%22+%22jolo%22#v=onepage&q=%22pershing%22%20%22medal%20of%20honor%22%20%22jolo%22&f=false |location=New York, NY |publisher=Doubleday, Page & Company |page=103 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121024253/https://books.google.com/books?id=6uRAAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA103&dq=%22pershing%22+%22medal+of+honor%22+%22jolo%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=poM6Ve7rOYLTggTv9oCQCA&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22pershing%22%20%22medal%20of%20honor%22%20%22jolo%22&f=false |archivedate=November 21, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  In 1922 a further review of this event resulted in Pershing being recommended for the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]], but as the [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Army Chief of Staff]] Pershing disapproved the action.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smythe |first=Donald |date=1973 |title=Guerrilla Warrior: The Early Life of John J. Pershing |url=https://books.google.com/?id=l4oLAAAAYAAJ&q=%22pershing%22+%22distinguished+service+cross%22+%221922%22&dq=%22pershing%22+%22distinguished+service+cross%22+%221922%22 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons |page=318 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128194332/https://books.google.com/books?id=l4oLAAAAYAAJ&q=%22pershing%22+%22distinguished+service+cross%22+%221922%22&dq=%22pershing%22+%22distinguished+service+cross%22+%221922%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=IIg6VbLrFsSegwSthIH4Aw&ved=0CEAQ6AEwBg |archivedate=November 28, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  In 1940 Pershing received the Distinguished Service Cross for his heroism at Bud Bagsak, with President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] presenting it in a ceremony timed to coincide with Pershing's 80th birthday.<ref>{{cite book |last=Jackson |first=Robert H. |date=2003 |title=That Man: An Insider's Portrait of Franklin D. Roosevelt |url=https://archive.org/details/thatmaninsidersp00jack |url-access=registration |quote=pershing distinguished service cross roosevelt birthday. |location=New York, NY |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/thatmaninsidersp00jack/page/130 130] |isbn=978-0-19-517757-2 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring this period Pershing's reputation for both stern discipline and effective leadership continued to grow, with one experienced old soldier under his command later saying Pershing was an \"[[Bitch (insult)#Son of a bitch|S.O.B.]]\" and that he hated Pershing's guts, but that \"as a soldier, the ones then and the ones now couldn't polish his (Pershing's) boots.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Frazer |first=Nimrod Thompson |date=2014 |title=Send the Alabamians: World War I Fighters in the Rainbow Division |url=https://books.google.com/?id=mbZiAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA18&dq=%22pershing%22+%22the+ones+then+and+the+ones+now%22#v=onepage&q=%22pershing%22%20%22the%20ones%20then%20and%20the%20ones%20now%22&f=false |location=Tuscaloosa, AL |publisher=University of Alabama Press |page=18 |isbn=978-0-8173-8769-3 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016210313/https://books.google.com/books?id=mbZiAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA18&dq=%22pershing%22+%22the+ones+then+and+the+ones+now%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qYo6VdL1LZPtgwTXooPICw&ved=0CCMQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22pershing%22%20%22the%20ones%20then%20and%20the%20ones%20now%22&f=false |archivedate=October 16, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Pancho Villa and Mexico==\n{{main|Pancho Villa Expedition}}\n[[File:Gen Obregon, Villa, Pershing at Ft Bliss 1914.jpg|thumb|175px|Generals [[\u00c1lvaro Obreg\u00f3n|Obreg\u00f3n]], [[Pancho Villa|Villa]], and Pershing, August 1914. A year later, Pershing's wife and three of his children died, and Villa sent him condolences. Six months later, Pershing chased Villa in Mexico.]]\n[[File:Nita Patton (Sister of General George S. Patton).jpg|thumb|175px|Nita Patton was engaged to Pershing in 1917\u201318.]]\n[[File:Camping on the Border, near El Paso, Texas.jpg|thumb|175px|Postcard of Pershing's camp at Fort Bliss.]]\n\nOn December 20, 1913, Pershing received orders to take command of the 8th Brigade at the [[Presidio of San Francisco|Presidio]] in [[San Francisco]]. With tensions running high on the border between the United States and Mexico, the brigade was deployed to [[Fort Bliss, Texas]] on April 24, 1914, arriving there on the 27th.<ref>Vandiver, Volume I, p. 582</ref>\n\n===Death of wife and children===\nAfter a year at Fort Bliss, Pershing decided to take his family there. The arrangements were almost complete, when on the morning of August 27, 1915, he received a telegram informing him of a fire in the [[Presidio of San Francisco|Presidio]] in [[San Francisco]], where a lacquered floor caught fire and the flames rapidly spread, resulting in the smoke inhalation deaths of his wife, Helen Frances Warren, and three young daughters, Mary, age 3, Anne, age 7, and Helen, age 8. Only his 6-year-old son, Francis Warren, survived.<ref>{{cite web|work=nps.gov|url=http://www.nps.gov/prsf/historyculture/john-pershing.htm|title=Pershing history and house photos|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711023105/http://www.nps.gov/prsf/historyculture/john-pershing.htm|archivedate=July 11, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>Vandiver, Volume I, pp. 593\u201394</ref> After the funerals at Lakeview Cemetery in Cheyenne, Wyoming, Pershing returned to Fort Bliss with his son, Francis, and his sister May and resumed his duties as commanding officer.<ref>Boot, p. 192</ref><ref>Vandiver, Volume II, pp. 599\u2013602</ref>\n\n===Relationship with Nita Patton===\nTwo years after the death of his wife and children, Pershing courted Anne Wilson \"Nita\" Patton, the younger sister of his prot\u00e9g\u00e9, [[George S. Patton]].<ref name=nita />  Pershing met her when she traveled to Fort Bliss to visit her brother,<ref name=blood>{{cite book |last=Keane |first=Michael |date=2012 |title=George S. Patton: Blood, Guts, and Prayer |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=byMjBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA71 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=Regnery History |pages=71\u201372 |isbn=978-1-62157-298-5}}</ref> and he introduced them.<ref name=blood /> Pershing and Nita Patton soon began a relationship; they became engaged in 1917, but their separation because of Pershing's time in France during World War I ended it.<ref name=nita>Vandiver, v.II, pp. 606, 608, 657\u201358, 666, 674, 684\u201387, 698, 735, 737, 791, 1008</ref><ref name=blood />  Pershing had wartime affairs, including one with French-Romanian Micheline Resco (1894\u20131968), an artist who painted his portrait, and he later expressed regret that he had let Nita Patton \"get away\".<ref>{{cite book |last=D'Este |first=Carlo |date=2002 |title=Eisenhower: A Soldier's Life |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g72pCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA191 |location=New York|publisher=Henry Holt |page=191 |isbn=978-0-8050-5687-7}}</ref>  Nita Patton never married, while Pershing remained unmarried until he secretly wed Resco in 1946.<ref name=blood /><ref name=\"news.unl.edu\">{{cite web |url=https://news.unl.edu/newsrooms/today/article/11-things-you-probably-didnt-know-about-john-j-pershing/ |title=11 things you probably didn't know about John J. Pershing  |last=Reed |first=Leslie |date=November 9, 2017 |website=Nebraska Today |publisher=University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln |location=Lincoln, Nebraska}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/2006/01/15/a-hospitals-storied-halls-span-classbankheadrelics-of-walter-reeds-famed-patients-face-uncertain-fate-span/5a183cc8-5dad-4b0b-ad3f-168ea45f4f78/|title=A Hospital's Storied Halls&nbsp;Relics of Walter Reed's Famed Patients Face Uncertain Fate|publisher=Washingtonpost.com|date=15 January 2006|accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Commander of Villa expedition===\nOn March 15, 1916,<ref name=\"history.army.mil\">{{cite web |url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/reference/army_flag/mexex.html |title=Mexican Expedition Campaign |publisher=History.army.mil |accessdate=2014-04-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718210806/http://www.history.army.mil/html/reference/army_flag/mexex.html |archivedate=July 18, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.archives.gov/publications/prologue/1997/fall/mexican-punitive-expedition-1.html |title=Prologue: Selected Articles |publisher=Archives.gov |accessdate=2014-04-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423065711/http://www.archives.gov/publications/prologue/1997/fall/mexican-punitive-expedition-1.html |archivedate=April 23, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Buffalo Soldiers at Huachuca: Organizing the Punitive Expedition |url=http://net.lib.byu.edu/estu/wwi/comment/huachuca/HI1-13.htm |journal=Huachuca Illustrated |volume=1 |year=1993 |accessdate=August 2, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618044540/http://net.lib.byu.edu/estu/wwi/comment/huachuca/HI1-13.htm |archivedate=June 18, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Pershing led an expedition into Mexico to capture [[Pancho Villa]]. This expedition was ill-equipped and hampered by a lack of supplies due to the breakdown of the Quartermaster Corps. Although there had been talk of war on the border for years, no steps had been taken to provide for the handling of supplies for an expedition. Despite this and other hindrances, such as the lack of aid from the former Mexican government, and their refusal to allow American troops to transport troops and supplies over their railroads, Pershing organized and commanded the [[Pancho Villa Expedition|Mexican Punitive Expedition]], a combined armed force of 10,000 men that penetrated {{convert|350|mi}} into Mexico. They routed Villa's revolutionaries, but failed to capture him.<ref>Boot, ''passim'' pp. 192\u2013204</ref><ref>Vandiver, Volume II, ''passim'' pp. 604\u201368</ref>\n\n==World War I==\n[[File:John Pershing, Bain bw photo as major general, 1917.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Major General Pershing of the [[National Army (USA)|National Army]]]]\n\nAt the start of the United States' involvement in [[World War I]] President [[Woodrow Wilson]] considered mobilizing an army to join the fight. [[Frederick Funston]], Pershing's superior in Mexico, was being considered for the top billet as the Commander of the American Expeditionary Force (AEF) when he died suddenly from a heart attack on February 19, 1917. Pershing was the most likely candidate other than Funston, and following America's entrance into the war in May, Wilson briefly interviewed Pershing, and then selected him for the command.  He was officially installed in the position on May 10, 1917, and held the post until 1918. On October&nbsp;6, 1917, Pershing, then a [[Major general (United States)|major general]], was promoted to full general in the [[National Army (USA)|National Army]].  He bypassed the three star rank of lieutenant general, and was the first full general since [[Philip Sheridan]] in 1888.  As AEF commander, Pershing was responsible for the organization, training, and supply of a combined professional and draft Army and National Guard force that eventually grew from 27,000 inexperienced men to two Armies, with a third forming as the war ended, totaling over two million soldiers.\n\nPershing exercised significant control over his command, with a full delegation of authority from Wilson and [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[Newton D. Baker]]. Baker, cognizant of the endless problems of domestic and allied political involvement in military decision making in wartime, gave Pershing unmatched authority to run his command as he saw fit. In turn, Pershing exercised his prerogative carefully, not engaging in politics or disputes over government policy that might distract him from his military mission. While earlier a champion of the African-American soldier, he did not advocate their full participation on the battlefield, understanding the general racial attitudes of white Americans. \n\n[[George Marshall]] served as one of Pershing's top assistants during and after the war. Pershing's initial chief of staff was [[James Harbord]], who later took a combat command but worked as Pershing's closest assistant for many years and remained extremely loyal to him.\n\n[[File:Pershing at Lafayette Tomb.jpg|left|thumb|282px|Pershing saluting the [[Gilbert du Motier, marquis de Lafayette|Marquis de Lafayette]]'s grave in [[Paris]]]]\n\nAfter departing from [[Fort Jay]] at [[Governors Island]] in New York Harbor under top secrecy in May 1917 aboard the [[RMS Baltic (1903)|RMS ''Baltic,'']] Pershing arrived in France in June 1917. In a show of American presence, part of the [[16th Infantry Regiment (United States)#World War I|16th Infantry Regiment]] marched through Paris shortly after his arrival. Pausing at the tomb of [[Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette]], he was reputed to have uttered the famous line \"Lafayette, we are here,\" a line spoken, in fact, by his aide, Colonel [[Charles E. Stanton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unc.edu/depts/diplomat/AD_Issues/amdipl_16/edit16_print.html|title=Mattox: Natural Allies|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070330165559/http://www.unc.edu/depts/diplomat/AD_Issues/amdipl_16/edit16_print.html|archivedate=March 30, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> American forces were deployed in France in the autumn of 1917.\n\nIn September 1917 the French government commissioned a portrait of Pershing by 23-year-old Romanian artist Micheline Resco.  Pershing removed the stars and flag from his car and sat up front with his chauffeur while traveling from his AEF headquarters to visit her by night in her apartment on the rue Descombes.  Their friendship continued for the rest of his life.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Fleming |first=Thomas |year=1995 |title=Iron General |journal=[[MHQ: The Quarterly Journal of Military History]] |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=66, 73 |publisher=American Historical Publications }}</ref> In 1946, at 85, Pershing secretly wed French-Romanian portrait artist Micheline Resco in his Walter Reed Hospital apartment. Resco was 35 years his junior<ref name=\"news.unl.edu\"/>\n\n===Battle of Hamel===\nFor the first time in American history, Pershing allowed American soldiers to be under the command of a foreign power. In late June, General [[Henry Rawlinson, 1st Baron Rawlinson|Rawlinson]], commanding the British Fourth Army, suggested to Australian Lieutenant General [[John Monash]] that American involvement in a set-piece attack alongside the experienced Australians in the upcoming [[Battle of Hamel]] would both give the American troops experience and also strengthen the Australian battalions by an additional company each. On June 29, General Bell, commanding the American 33rd Division, selected two companies each from the 131st and 132nd Infantry regiments of the 66th brigade. Monash had been promised ten companies of American troops and on June 30 the remaining companies of the 1st and 2nd battalions of the 131st regiment were sent. Each American platoon was attached to an Australian company, but there was difficulty in integrating the American platoons (which numbered 60 men) among the Australian companies of 100 men. This difficulty was overcome by reducing the size of each American platoon by one-fifth and sending the troops thus removed, which numbered 50 officers and men, back to battalion reinforcement camps.\n\nThe day before the attack was scheduled to commence, Pershing learned of the plan and ordered the withdrawal of six American companies.<ref name=\"Nunan, Peter 2000\">Nunan, Peter (2000). \"Diggers' Fourth of July\". ''Military History''. 17 (3): 26\u201332 & 80. {{ISSN|0889-7328}}</ref> While a few Americans, such as those attached to the 42nd Battalion, disobeyed the order, the majority, although disappointed, moved back to the rear. This meant that battalions had to rearrange their attack formations and caused a serious reduction in the size of the Allied force. For example, the 11th Brigade was now attacking with 2,200 men instead of 3,000.<ref>Bean, C.E.W (1942). The Australian Imperial Force in France during the Allied Offensive, 1918. Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918. Volume VI. Sydney, New South Wales: Angus and Robertson. OCLC 41008291</ref> There was a further last-minute call for the removal of all American troops from the attack, but Monash, who had chosen 4 July as the date of the attack out of \"deference\" to the US troops, protested to Rawlinson and received support from Field Marshal Douglas Haig, commander of the British Expeditionary Force.<ref name=\"Nunan, Peter 2000\"/><ref>an, C.E.W (1942). The Australian Imperial Force in France during the Allied Offensive, 1918. Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918. Volume VI. Sydney, New South Wales: Angus and Robertson. OCLC 41008291</ref> The four American companies that had joined the Australians during the assault were withdrawn from the line after the battle and returned to their regiments, having gained valuable experience. Monash sent Bell his personal thanks, praising the Americans' gallantry, while Pershing set out explicit instructions to ensure that US troops would not be employed in a similar manner again.<ref name=\"Nunan, Peter 2000\"/>\n\n===African-American units===\nUnder [[civilian control of the military]], Pershing adhered to the racial policies of [[President of the United States|President]] [[Woodrow Wilson]], [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[Newton D. Baker]], and southern Democrats who promoted the \"[[separate but equal]]\" doctrine. African-American \"[[Buffalo Soldier]]s\" units were not allowed to participate with the [[American Expeditionary Forces|American Expeditionary Force (AEF)]] during [[World War I]], but experienced [[non-commissioned officer]]s were provided to other segregated black units for combat service\u2014such as the 317th Engineer Battalion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/lineages/branches/eng/0317enbn.htm |title=Lineage and Honors Information, 317th Engineer Battalion |website=history.army.mil/ |publisher=US Army Center of Military History |access-date=October 2, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111203615/http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/lineages/branches/eng/0317enbn.htm |archivedate=November 11, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The American Buffalo Soldiers of the [[92nd Infantry Division (United States)|92nd]] and [[93rd Infantry Division (United States)|93rd Infantry Divisions]] were the first American soldiers to fight in France in 1918, but they did so under French command as Pershing had detached them from the AEF. Most regiments of the 92nd and all of the 93rd would continue to fight under French command for the duration of the war.<ref name=\"Buckley\">{{Citation| author=Buckley, Gail Lumet| title=American Patriots: The Story of Blacks in the Military from the Revolution to Desert Storm| location=| publisher=Random House| year=2001| id=| isbn=978-0-375-50279-8| url=https://archive.org/details/americanpatriots00buck| url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n==World War I: 1918 and full American participation==\n[[File:John Pershing.jpg|thumb|175px|right|Pershing at General Headquarters in [[Chaumont (Haute-Marne)|Chaumont]], France, October 1918.]]\n\nIn early 1918, entire divisions were beginning to serve on the front lines alongside French troops. Pershing insisted that the AEF fight as units under American command rather than being split up by battalions to augment British and French regiments and brigades (although the [[27th Infantry Division (United States)|27th]] and [[30th Infantry Division (United States)|30th Divisions]], grouped under [[II Corps (United States)|II Corps]] command, were loaned during the [[Spring Offensive|desperate days of spring 1918]], fought with the British/Australian/Canadian [[Fourth Army (United Kingdom)|Fourth Army]] until the end of the war, taking part in the breach of the [[Hindenburg Line]] in October).\n\nBy May 1918, Pershing had become discontented with [[Air Service, United States Army|Air Service of the American Expeditionary Force]], believing staff planning had been inefficient with considerable internal dissension, as well as conflict between its members and those of Pershing's General Staff. Further, aircraft and unit totals lagged far behind those expected. Pershing appointed his former [[West Point]] classmate and non-aviator, [[Major General]] [[Mason Patrick]] as the new [[United States Army Air Service#Chiefs, AEF Aviation|Chief of Air Service]]. Considerable house-cleaning of the existing staff resulted from Patrick's appointment, bringing in experienced staff officers to administrate, and tightening up lines of communication.<ref>Tate, Dr. James P. (1998). ''The Army and its Air Corps: Army Policy Toward Aviation 1919\u20131941'', Air University Press, p. 19</ref><ref name=\"DuPre\">{{cite web |url= https://www.af.mil/About-Us/Biographies/Display/Article/105991/major-general-mason-m-patrick/|title=U.S. Air Force Biographical Dictionary |last=DuPre |first=Flint |date= |website= United States Air Force |publisher= |access-date=July 12, 2019 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1918, Pershing saw the need for a dedicated [[Military Police Corps (United States)|Military Police Corps]] and the first U.S. Army MP School was established at Autun, France. For this, he is considered the founding father of the United States MPs.<ref>Wright, Robert K. Jr. (ed.) ''[http://www.history.army.mil/books/Lineage/mp/mp.htm Army Lineage Series:Military Police] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117192807/http://www.history.army.mil/books/Lineage/mp/mp.htm |date=November 17, 2011 }}''</ref>\n\nBecause of the effects of [[trench warfare]] on soldiers' feet, in January 1918, Pershing oversaw the creation of an improved [[combat boot]], the \"[[Trench boot|1918 Trench Boot]],\" which became known as the \"Pershing Boot\" upon its introduction.<ref name=lt>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldwar1.com/dbc/l_tanks.htm|title=The American Field Shoe|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815103701/http://www.worldwar1.com/dbc/l_tanks.htm|archivedate=August 15, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAmerican forces first saw serious action during the summer of 1918, contributing eight large divisions, alongside 24 French ones, at the [[Second Battle of the Marne]]. Along with the British Fourth Army's victory at [[Battle of Amiens (1918)|Amiens]], the Allied victory at the Second Battle of the Marne marked the turning point of World War I on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]].\n\nIn August 1918 the [[First United States Army|U.S. First Army]] had been formed, first under Pershing's direct command and then by Lieutenant General [[Hunter Liggett]], when the [[Second United States Army|U.S. Second Army]] under Lieutenant General [[Robert Lee Bullard|Robert Bullard]] was created. After a quick victory at [[Battle of Saint-Mihiel|Saint-Mihiel]], east of [[Verdun]], some of the more bullish AEF commanders had hoped to push on eastwards to [[Metz]], but this did not fit in with the plans of the Allied Supreme Commander, [[Ferdinand Foch|Marshal Foch]], for three simultaneous offensives into the \"bulge\" of the Western Front (the other two being the Fourth Army's breach of the Hindenburg Line and an Anglo-Belgian offensive, led by [[Herbert Plumer, 1st Viscount Plumer|Plumer's]] Second Army, in Flanders). Instead, the AEF was required to redeploy and, aided by French tanks, launched a major offensive northwards in very difficult terrain at [[Meuse-Argonne Offensive|Meuse-Argonne]]. Initially enjoying numerical odds of eight to one, this offensive eventually engaged 35 or 40 of the 190 or so German divisions on the Western Front, although to put this in perspective, around half the German divisions were engaged on the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War I)|British Expeditionary Force]] (BEF) sector at the time.\n\n[[File:Stars and Stripes first issue.tif|thumb|left|Pershing on the front page of the first issue of ''[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]'', February 8, 1918.]]\n\nThe offensive was marked by a Pershing failure, specifically his reliance on massed infantry attacks with little artillery support led to high casualty rates in the capturing of three key points. This was despite the AEF facing only second-line German troops after the decision by [[Erich Ludendorff]], the [[German General Staff|German Chief of Staff]], to withdraw to the Hindenburg Line on October 3\u2013and in notable contrast to the simultaneous British breakthrough of the Hindenburg Line in the north. Pershing was subsequently forced to reorganize the AEF with the creation of the Second Army, and to step down as the commander of the First Army.<ref>Trask, David F. ''The AEF and Coalition Warmaking, 1917\u20131918''. [[University Press of Kansas]], 1993, p. 141.</ref>\n\nWhen he arrived in Europe, Pershing had openly scorned the slow trench warfare of the previous three years on the Western Front, believing that American soldiers' skill with the rifle would enable them to avoid costly and senseless fighting over a small area of [[no-man's land]]. This was regarded as unrealistic by British and French commanders, and (privately) by a number of Americans such as [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Army Chief of Staff]] General [[Tasker H. Bliss|Tasker Bliss]] and even Liggett. Even German generals were negative, with Ludendorff dismissing Pershing's strategic efforts in the Meuse-Argonne offensive by recalling how \"the attacks of the youthful American troops broke down with the heaviest losses\".<ref>Trask, David F. ''The AEF and Coalition Warmaking, 1917\u20131918''. University Press of Kansas, 1993, p. 142.</ref> The AEF had performed well in the relatively open warfare of the Second Battle of the Marne, but the eventual American casualties against German defensive positions in the Argonne (roughly 120,000 American casualties in six weeks, against 35 or 40 German divisions) were not noticeably better than those of the Franco-British [[Battle of the Somme|offensive on the Somme]] two years earlier (600,000 casualties in four and a half months, versus 50 or so German divisions). More ground was gained, but by this stage of the war the [[German Army (German Empire)|German Army]] was in worse shape than in previous years.\n\n{{Listen\n|filename=Pershing - Address from France.ogg\n|title=\"Address from France\"\n|description=A speech given from Allied Headquarters, Chaumont, France, 1918\n}}\n\nSome writers<ref>e.g., David F. Trask (1993)</ref> have speculated that Pershing's frustration at the slow progress through the Argonne was the cause of two incidents which then ensued. First, he ordered the U.S. First Army to take \"the honor\" of recapturing [[Sedan, France|Sedan]], site of the [[Battle of Sedan|French defeat in 1870]]; the ensuing confusion (an order was issued that \"boundaries were not to be considered binding\") exposed American troops to danger not only from the French on their left, but even from one another, as the [[1st Infantry Division (United States)|1st Division]] tacked westward by night across the path of the [[42nd Infantry Division (United States)|42nd Division]] (accounts differ as to whether [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[Douglas MacArthur]], then commanding the 84th Brigade of the 42nd Division, was really mistaken for a German officer and arrested). Liggett, who had been away from headquarters the previous day, had to sort out the mess and implement the instructions from the Allied Supreme Command, Marshal Foch, allowing the French to recapture the city; he later recorded that this was the only time during the war in which he lost his temper.\n\nSecond, Pershing sent an unsolicited letter to the Allied [[Supreme War Council]], demanding that the Germans not be given an armistice and that instead, the Allies should push on and obtain an unconditional surrender.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Pershing and the Armistice|author=Lowry, Bullitt|journal=[[The Journal of American History]]|volume=55|pages=281\u2013291|number=2|date=September 1968|jstor=1899558|doi=10.2307/1899558}}</ref> Although in later years, many, including President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], felt that Pershing had been correct, at the time, this was a breach of political authority. Pershing narrowly escaped a serious reprimand from Wilson's aide, [[Edward M. House|\"Colonel\" Edward M. House]], and later apologized.{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n\n[[File:Gen Pershing decorating soldiers in Trier c1919.jpg|thumb|right|General Pershing decorating soldiers in Trier, 1919.]]\n\nAt the time of the [[Armistice of 11 November 1918|Armistice]], another Franco-American offensive was due to start on November 14, thrusting towards [[Metz]] and into [[Lorraine]], to take place simultaneously with further BEF advances through [[Belgium]].\n\nIn his memoirs, Pershing claimed that the American breakout from the Argonne at the start of November was the decisive event leading to the [[Germany|German]] acceptance of an armistice, because it made untenable the Antwerp\u2013Meuse line. This is probably an exaggeration; the outbreak of civil unrest and naval mutiny in Germany, the collapse of [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]], the [[Ottoman Empire]], and particularly [[Austria-Hungary]] following [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] victories in [[Thessaloniki|Salonika]], Syria, and Italy, and the Allied victories on the Western Front were among a series of events in the autumn of 1918 which made it clear that Allied victory was inevitable, and diplomatic inquiries about an armistice had been going on throughout October. President Wilson was keen to tie matters up before the mid-term elections,{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} and as the other Allies were running low on supplies and manpower,<ref>{{cite book |last=Peare |first=Catherine Owens |date=1963 |title=The Woodrow Wilson Story: An Idealist in Politics |url=https://books.google.com/?id=q9UEAQAAIAAJ&q=%22the+war+in+Europe+at+the+time+that+the+United+States+became+an+associate+of+the+Allies+was+still+at+a+stalemate.+The+Allied+countries+were+reaching+the+exhaustion+of+both+men+and+supplies%22&dq=%22the+war+in+Europe+at+the+time+that+the+United+States+became+an+associate+of+the+Allies+was+still+at+a+stalemate.+The+Allied+countries+were+reaching+the+exhaustion+of+both+men+and+supplies%22 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Thomas Y. Crowell Co. |page=235 |quote=The war in Europe at the time that the United States became an associate of the Allies was still at a stalemate. The Allied countries were reaching the exhaustion of both men and supplies ...|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430074304/https://books.google.com/books?id=q9UEAQAAIAAJ&q=%22the+war+in+Europe+at+the+time+that+the+United+States+became+an+associate+of+the+Allies+was+still+at+a+stalemate.+The+Allied+countries+were+reaching+the+exhaustion+of+both+men+and+supplies%22&dq=%22the+war+in+Europe+at+the+time+that+the+United+States+became+an+associate+of+the+Allies+was+still+at+a+stalemate.+The+Allied+countries+were+reaching+the+exhaustion+of+both+men+and+supplies%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj3k6aTw8jJAhXCPD4KHc2VAjMQ6AEIHDAA |archivedate=April 30, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> they followed Wilson's lead.{{Citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n[[File:Pershing and his General Staff at Headquarters, Chaumont.jpg|thumb|left|Pershing and his General Staff at Headquarters, Chaumont.]]\n\nAmerican successes were largely credited to Pershing, and he became the most celebrated American leader of the war. MacArthur saw Pershing as a desk soldier, and the relationship between the two men deteriorated by the end of the war. Similar criticism of senior commanders by the younger generation of officers (the future generals of [[World War II]]) was made in the British and other armies, but in fairness to Pershing, although it was not uncommon for brigade commanders to serve near the front and even be killed, the state of communications in World War I made it more practical for senior generals to command from the rear. He controversially ordered his troops to continue fighting before the signed Armistice took effect. This resulted in 3,500 American casualties on the last day of the war, an act which was regarded as murder by a few officers under his command. Pershing doubted the German\u2019s good faith, and most of his contemporaries took the view he expressed to the House Committee on Military Affairs in his testimony on November 5, 1919:\n\n\u201cWhen the subject of the armistice was under discussion we did not know what the purpose of it was definitely, whether it was something proposed by the German High Command to gain time or whether they were sincere in their desire to have an armistice; and the mere discussion of an armistice would not be sufficient grounds for any judicious commander to relax his military activities\u2026.No one could possibly know when the armistice was to be signed, or what hour be fixed for the cessation of hostilities so that the only thing for us to do, and which I did as commander in chief of the American forces, and which Marshal Foch did as commander in chief of the Allied armies was to continue the military activities\u2026.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historynet.com/world-war-i-wasted-lives-on-armistice-day.htm|title=World War I: Wasted Lives on Armistice Day|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515085844/http://www.historynet.com/world-war-i-wasted-lives-on-armistice-day.htm|archivedate=May 15, 2011|df=mdy-all|date=2006-06-12}}</ref>\n\nThe year of 1918 also saw a personal health struggle for Pershing as he was sickened during the [[1918 flu pandemic]], but unlike many who were not so fortunate, Pershing survived.<ref>Collier, Richard. ''The Plague of the Spanish Lady: The Influenza Pandemic of 1918\u20131919'' (Atheneum, 1974)</ref> He rode his horse, Kidron, in the Paris victory parade in 1919.<ref>{{cite news |author=United Press |title=Gen. Pershing's Horse Dies |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F01E5DA1339E33BBC4B52DFB6678389659EDE |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 13, 1942 |accessdate=2015-02-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207065157/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F01E5DA1339E33BBC4B52DFB6678389659EDE |archivedate=February 7, 2015 |df=mdy-all |author-link=United Press }}</ref>{{clear left}}\n\n==Later career==\n[[File:GEN Pershing as Chief Of Staff.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Gen. Pershing as Army Chief of Staff]]\n\nIn September 1919, in recognition of his distinguished service during World War I, the [[Congress of the United States|U.S. Congress]] authorized the President to promote Pershing to [[General of the Armies of the United States]], the highest rank possible for any member of the United States armed forces, which was created especially for him.<ref>{{cite book |last=McCarl |first=J. R. |date=1925 |title=Decisions of the Comptroller General of the United States |volume=4 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=iAEWAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA317&dq=%22john+j+pershing%22+%22promoted%22+%221919%22#v=onepage&q=%22john%20j%20pershing%22%20%22promoted%22%20%221919%22&f=false |location=Washington, DC |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |page=317 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430074942/https://books.google.com/books?id=iAEWAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA317&dq=%22john+j+pershing%22+%22promoted%22+%221919%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwis-e3wrMDLAhVI2T4KHY4sC-c4ChDoAQghMAE#v=onepage&q=%22john%20j%20pershing%22%20%22promoted%22%20%221919%22&f=false |archivedate=April 30, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  (In 1976, Congress authorized President [[Gerald Ford]] to posthumously promote [[George Washington]] to this rank as part of the [[United States Bicentennial]]; Washington previously held the rank of [[General (United States)|General]] in the [[Continental Army]], and wore a three-star insignia;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://allthingsliberty.com/2013/09/clarifying-washingtons-rank/ |title=Clarifying Washington's Rank |last=Welsch |first=William |date=September 16, 2013 |website=allthingsliberty.com/ |publisher=Journal of the American Revolution |location=Naperville, IL |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012201821/https://allthingsliberty.com/2013/09/clarifying-washingtons-rank/ |archivedate=October 12, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> his posthumous appointment to General of the Armies rank and the specific wording of the authorizing statute, Public Law 94-479,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Public_Law_94-479|title=Public Law 94-479 - Wikisource, the free online library|website=en.wikisource.org|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> of October 1976, ensured that Washington would always be considered the U.S. Army's highest-ranking officer.)<ref>{{cite book |last=Oliver |first=Raymond |date=2007 |title=Why Is a Colonel Called a Kernal? the Origin of American Ranks and Insignia |url=https://books.google.com/?id=9TcKmEs-I_UC&pg=PA52&dq=%22george+washington%22+%221976%22+%22general+of+the+armies%22+%22promotion%22#v=onepage&q=%22george%20washington%22%20%221976%22%20%22general%20of%20the%20armies%22%20%22promotion%22&f=false |location=Tucson, AZ |publisher=Fireship Press |page=52 |isbn=978-1-934757-59-8 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506180933/https://books.google.com/books?id=9TcKmEs-I_UC&pg=PA52&dq=%22george+washington%22+%221976%22+%22general+of+the+armies%22+%22promotion%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj6qsWMp8DLAhWC2T4KHasHD-IQ6AEIMzAB#v=onepage&q=%22george%20washington%22%20%221976%22%20%22general%20of%20the%20armies%22%20%22promotion%22&f=false |archivedate=May 6, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Jenks |first=J. E., editor |date=April 9, 1921 |title=Generals of the Army |url=https://books.google.com/?id=CFM-AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA403&dq=%22pershing%22+%22promotion%22+%221919%22+%22general+of+the%22#v=onepage&q=%22general%20of%20the%22&f=false |journal=Army and Navy Register |location=Washington, DC |publisher=Army and Navy Publishing Company |page=351 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430071203/https://books.google.com/books?id=CFM-AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA403&dq=%22pershing%22+%22promotion%22+%221919%22+%22general+of+the%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwimnc7QqMDLAhXGeT4KHfNvDd04ChDoAQggMAE#v=onepage&q=%22general%20of%20the%22&f=false |archivedate=April 30, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Pershing was authorized to create his insignia for the new rank and chose to wear four gold stars<ref>{{cite news |date=December 11, 1919 |title=Program of Gen. Pershing Today; Many Interesting Events are Planned |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/26966420/ |newspaper=Atlanta Constitution |location=Atlanta, GA |page=7 |url-access=subscription  |quote=Immediately before the parade starts the general will be presented with a handsome general's flag, bearing four gold stars, by the Girls' Overseas club. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116131230/https://www.newspapers.com/image/26966420/ |archivedate=January 16, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=November 10, 1934 |title=Welfare of Soldiers and Graves of Heroes Claim Pershing Time |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/53486066/ |newspaper=The Daily Notes |location=Canonsburg, Pennsylvania |page=1 |url-access=subscription  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116131225/https://www.newspapers.com/image/53486066/ |archivedate=January 16, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Associated Press |date=April 28, 1937 |title=Pershing to Attend Coronation in Snappy Attire of Own Design |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/45926981/ |newspaper=Gettysburg Times |location=Gettysburg, Pennsylvania |page=2 |url-access=subscription  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065235/http://www.newspapers.com/image/45926981/ |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all |author-link=Associated Press }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Perrenot |first=Preston B. |date=2009 |title=United States Army Grade Insignia Since 1776 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ShHDSFJ4gPYC&pg=PA90&lpg=PA90&dq=%22pershing%22+%22gold%22+%22stars%22+%22general+of+the%22#v=onepage&q=%22pershing%22%20%22gold%22%20%22stars%22%20%22general%20of%20the%22&f=false |location=Scotts Valley, California |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform |page=90 |isbn=978-1-4486-5687-5 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430080808/https://books.google.com/books?id=ShHDSFJ4gPYC&pg=PA90&lpg=PA90&dq=%22pershing%22+%22gold%22+%22stars%22+%22general+of+the%22&source=bl&ots=CcDFr3BA8o&sig=ZESL7hOYEtrvhuBLl932CxxvFs8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwilgYCV6ZLKAhVFLyYKHeDkCNAQ6AEITDAH#v=onepage&q=%22pershing%22%20%22gold%22%20%22stars%22%20%22general%20of%20the%22&f=false |archivedate=April 30, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> for the rest of his career, which distinguished his insignia from the four (temporary) silver stars worn by Army Chiefs of Staff of the 1910s and early 1920s.<ref>{{cite book |last=Tucker |first=Spencer C. |date=2014 |title=World War I: The Definitive Encyclopedia and Document Collection |volume=I, A-C |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DBwTBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1721 |location=Santa Barbara, CA |publisher=ABC-CLIO |page=1721 |isbn=978-1-85109-964-1}}</ref>\n\nIn 1919, Pershing created the [[Military Order of the World Wars|Military Order of the World War]] as an officer's fraternity for veterans of the First World War, modeled after the [[Military Order of Foreign Wars]].  Both organizations still exist today and welcome new officer members to their ranks.  Pershing himself would join the MOFW in 1924.\n\nThere was a movement to draft Pershing as a candidate for president in 1920; he refused to campaign, but indicated that he \"wouldn't decline to serve\" if the people wanted him.<ref>{{cite book |last=Yockelson |first=Mitchell |date=2016 |title=Forty-Seven Days: How Pershing's Warriors Came of Age to Defeat the German Army in World War I |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cRbZCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA324 |location=New York, NY |publisher=NAL Caliber |page=324 |isbn=978-0-451-46695-2}}</ref> Though Pershing was a Republican, many of his party's leaders considered him too closely tied to the policies of the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party's]] President Wilson.<ref>{{cite book |last=Fleming |first=Thomas |date=2003 |title=The Illusion Of Victory: America In World War I |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a6OTYMWr8S4C&pg=RA1-PA51 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Basic Books |page=451 |isbn=978-0-465-02467-4}}</ref> Another general, [[Leonard Wood]], was the early [[1920 Republican National Convention|Republican front runner]], but the nomination went to Senator [[Warren G. Harding]] of [[Ohio]], who went on to win the [[1920 U.S. presidential election|general election]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hodge |first1=Carl Cavanagh |last2=Nolan |first2=Cathal J. |date=2007 |title=US Presidents and Foreign Policy from 1789 to the Present |url=https://books.google.com/?id=qXeRALIwozgC&pg=PA226&dq=%22leonard+wood%22+%22president%22+%221920%22#v=onepage&q=%22leonard%20wood%22%20%22president%22%20%221920%22&f=false |location=Santa Barbara, CA |publisher=ABC-CLIO |page=226 |isbn=978-1-85109-790-6 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429080201/https://books.google.com/books?id=qXeRALIwozgC&pg=PA226&dq=%22leonard+wood%22+%22president%22+%221920%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIyJms65LKAhVM4SYKHUMWBvgQ6AEISDAI#v=onepage&q=%22leonard%20wood%22%20%22president%22%20%221920%22&f=false |archivedate=April 29, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:PershingVictoryMemorialKC crop.jpg|thumb|150px|Bronze relief of Pershing, Kansas City, Missouri, [[Liberty Memorial]]]]\n\nIn 1921, Pershing became [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]], serving for three years. He created the [[Pershing Map]], a proposed national network of military and civilian highways. The [[Interstate Highway System]] instituted in 1956 bears considerable resemblance to the Pershing map. On his 64th birthday, September 13, 1924, Pershing retired from active military service.  (Army regulations from the late 1860s to the early 1940s required officers to retire on their 64th birthday.)\n\nOn November 1, 1921, Pershing was in [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] to take part in the groundbreaking ceremony for the Liberty Memorial that was being constructed there, (now known as the [[National World War I Museum and Memorial]]). Also present that day were Lieutenant General [[Jules Marie Alphonse Jacques de Dixmude|Baron Jacques]] of Belgium, Admiral of the Fleet [[David Beatty, 1st Earl Beatty|David Beatty]] of Great Britain, Marshal [[Ferdinand Foch]] of France, and General [[Armando Diaz]] of Italy. One of the main speakers was Vice President [[Calvin Coolidge]]. In 1935, bas-reliefs of Pershing, Jacques, Foch and Diaz by sculptor [[Walker Hancock]] were added to the memorial.  Pershing also laid the cornerstone of the [[Indiana War Memorial#The War Memorial|World War Memorial]] in Indianapolis on July 4, 1927.<ref>{{cite book|last=Price|first=Nelson|title=Indianapolis Then & Now|publisher=Thunder Bay Press|location=San Diego, California|year=2004|pages=102\u201303|isbn=978-1-59223-208-6}}</ref>\n\nOn October 2, 1922, amid several hundred officers, many of them combat veterans of World War I, Pershing formally established the [[Reserve Officers Association]] (ROA) as an organization at the Willard Hotel in Washington, D.C. ROA is a 75,000-member, professional association of officers, former officers, and spouses of all the uniformed services of the United States, primarily the Reserve and United States National Guard. It is a congressionally chartered Association that advises the Congress and the President on issues of national security on behalf of all members of the Reserve Component.\n\nIn 1924 Pershing became a member of the Pennsylvania Society of the [[Sons of the American Revolution]].  He was also an honorary member of the [[Society of the Cincinnati]] and a Veteran Companion of the [[Military Order of Foreign Wars]].\n\n[[File:John Pershing Newsreel 1940.ogv|thumb|left|1940 newsreel]]\n\nPershing served on a committee of the [[Sons of the American Revolution]] to establish and recognize [[Constitution Day (United States)|Constitution Day]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite book |editor=Williams, Winston C. |title=Centennial History of the National Society of the Sons of the American Revolution 1889\u20131989 |publisher=Turner Publishing Company |location=Paducah, Kentucky |page=9 |year=1991 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0SHHzcZnVwEC |accessdate=January 15, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231132048/http://books.google.com/books?id=0SHHzcZnVwEC |archivedate=December 31, 2013 |df=mdy-all |isbn=9781563110283 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1930s, Pershing largely retreated to private life, but returned to the public eye with publication of his memoirs, ''[[My Experiences in the World War]]'', which were awarded the 1932 [[Pulitzer Prize]] for history. He was also an active [[Civitan International|Civitan]] during this time.<ref>{{cite book |last= Leonhart |first= James Chancellor |title= The Fabulous Octogenarian |year= 1962 |publisher= Redwood House, Inc. |location= Baltimore Maryland |page= 277 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1940, before and after the [[Fall of France]], Pershing was an outspoken advocate of aid for the [[United Kingdom]] during [[World War II]]. In August 1940, he publicly supported the \"[[Destroyers for Bases Agreement]]\", whereby the United States sold fifty warships from World War I to the UK in exchange for lengthy leases of land on British possessions for the establishment for military bases.\n\nIn 1944, with Congress' creation of the five star rank of General of the Army, Pershing was still considered to be the highest-ranking officer of the United States military as his rank was General of the Armies. \"In [1799] Congress created for [[George Washington]] the rank of General of the Armies ... General [[Ulysses S. Grant|[Ulysses S.] Grant]] received the title of General of the Army in 1866 . ... Carefully Congress wrote a bill (HR 7594) to revive the rank of General of the Armies for General Pershing alone to hold during his lifetime.  The rank would cease to exist upon Pershing's death.\" Later, when asked if this made Pershing a five-star general, [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[Henry L. Stimson]] commented that it did not, since Pershing never wore more than four stars, but that Pershing was still to be considered senior to the present five-star generals of World War II.<ref>{{cite book |last=Cray |first=Ed |date=1990 |title=General of the Army: George C. Marshall, Soldier and Statesman |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Gwq6WvWxe6oC&pg=PA491&dq=%22stimson%22+%22pershing%22+%22five+star%22#v=onepage&q=%22stimson%22%20%22pershing%22%20%22five%20star%22&f=false |location=New York, NY |publisher=Cooper Square Press |page=491 |isbn=978-0-8154-1042-3 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430075028/https://books.google.com/books?id=Gwq6WvWxe6oC&pg=PA491&dq=%22stimson%22+%22pershing%22+%22five+star%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjO-JmVwbjKAhVEmh4KHYoxBBoQ6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=%22stimson%22%20%22pershing%22%20%22five%20star%22&f=false |archivedate=April 30, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn July 1944, Pershing was visited by [[Free French]] leader General [[Charles de Gaulle]]. When Pershing asked after the health of his old friend, Marshal [[Philippe P\u00e9tain]] \u2013 who had headed the pro-German [[Vichy France|Vichy]] regime until it was dissolved in late 1942 \u2013 de Gaulle replied tactfully that, when he last saw him, the Marshal was well.<ref>{{cite book |authorlink=Roy Jenkins |first=Roy |last=Jenkins |title=Churchill: A Biography |publisher=Farrar, Straus & Giroux |year=2001 |page=[https://archive.org/details/churchillbiograp00jenk/page/743 743] |location=New York |isbn=978-0-374-12354-3 |oclc=47658851 |url=https://archive.org/details/churchillbiograp00jenk/page/743 }}</ref>{{clear left}}\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Pershing's Tombstone.jpg|thumb|200px|Pershing's tombstone at [[Arlington National Cemetery]]]]\n\nOn July 15, 1948, Pershing died of [[coronary artery disease]] and [[congestive heart failure]] at [[Walter Reed Army Medical Center|Walter Reed General Hospital]] in Washington, D.C., which was his home after 1944. He [[lying in state#United States|lay in state]] at the [[United States Capitol rotunda]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aoc.gov/nations-stage/lying-state-honor |title= Lying in State or in Honor |publisher=US Architect of the Capitol (AOC) |accessdate=2018-09-01}}</ref> and following a [[state funeral]], he was buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]],<ref>[https://archive.org/details/papersofgeorgeca02mars/page/505 <!--  quote=pershing state funeral arlington. --> ''The Papers of George Catlett Marshall'']</ref> near the grave sites of the soldiers he commanded in Europe. The site is now known as Pershing Hill.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mossman |first1=B. C. |last2=Stark |first2=M. W. |date=1991 |title=The Last Salute: Civil and Military Funerals, 1921-1969 |url=https://history.army.mil/books/Last_Salute/Ch4.htm |location=Washington, DC |publisher=Department of the Army |page=44}}</ref> [[George Marshall|George C. Marshall]], then serving as U.S. Secretary of State, was in charge of funeral plans.<ref>{{Cite book|title=George Marshall: Defender of the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YjR1DwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover|last=Roll|first=David|publisher=Penguin Random House |location=New York, NY |year=2019 |isbn=978-1-1019-9097-1 |page=525 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIt was during his initial assignment in the American West that Pershing's mother died.<ref name=\"ParentsDoD\">Vandiver, v.1, p. 388</ref> On March 16, 1906, his father died.<ref name=\"ParentsDoD\"/> In 1946, Pershing secretly wed French-Romanian portrait artist Micheline Resco in his [[Walter Reed Hospital]] apartment.<ref name=Mead>{{cite book |last=Mead |first=Gary |date=2001 |title=The Doughboys: America and the First World War |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Kk4pAQAAMAAJ&dq=pershing+married+Micheline+Resco&q=%22On+2+September+1946+Micheline+Resco+and+John+Pershing+were+quietly+married+in+the+hospital%22 |location=Westminster, London, England |publisher=Penguin Books |page=112 |isbn=978-0-14-026490-6}}</ref>  Resco was 35 years his junior and they had known each other and exchanged encoded love letters since meeting in [[Paris]] in 1917, where Resco painted Pershing's portrait.<ref name=\"Mead\"/>\n\nColonel Francis Warren Pershing (1909\u20131980), John J. Pershing's son, served in the [[Second World War]] as an advisor to the Army Chief of Staff, General [[George C. Marshall]]. After the war he continued with his financial career and founded a stock brokerage firm, [[Pershing LLC|Pershing & Company]]. In 1938, he married Muriel Bache Richards, granddaughter of financier [[Jules Bache]].<ref>{{Cite web|first= |last= |authorlink=   |title= The General Attends a Wedding - His Son Marries Muriel Bache Richards  |publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date= May 2, 1938|url=https://books.google.com/?id=00oEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA11&lpg=PA11&dq=%22Frederick+Lloyd+Richards%22#v=onepage&q=%22Frederick%20Lloyd%20Richards%22&f=false  |accessdate=}}</ref> He was father to two sons, Richard W. Pershing (1942\u20131968) and John Warren Pershing III (1941\u20131999). Richard Pershing  served as a second lieutenant  in the [[502nd Infantry]] and was killed in action on February 17, 1968, in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/richardw.htm|title=Arlington Cemetery records: Richard Warren Pershing|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060616173158/http://arlingtoncemetery.net/richardw.htm|archivedate=June 16, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref> John Pershing III served as a special assistant to former Army Chief of Staff General [[Gordon R. Sullivan]], also attaining the rank of [[colonel]].  He helped shape army and the [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps|ROTC]] programs nationwide.  Colonel Pershing died of cardiovascular disease in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/jwpershing.htm|title=Arlington Cemetery records: John Warren Pershing III|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070312115707/http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/jwpershing.htm|archivedate=March 12, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Summary of service==\n\n===Dates of rank===\nThe table, below, does not identify General Pershing as having held the rank of Lieutenant General, though other articles & photo captions can be found that associate him with this rank. It is possible that he was promoted to that rank in the Regular Army, but directly to the rank of (four-star) General in the National Army that was formed specifically to fight WWI. Also, General Pershing was promoted, by Congress, to the rank of General of the Armies, superior to the 5-star rank of General of the Army, without having held the inferior rank:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! Insignia !! Rank !! Component !! Date\n|-\n| ''No Insignia'' || [[Cadet#United States|Cadet]] || [[United States Military Academy]] || July 1, 1882\n|-\n| ''No Insignia in 1886'' || [[Second lieutenant#United States|Second Lieutenant]] || 6th Cavalry, [[Regular Army (United States)|Regular Army]] || July 1, 1886\n|-\n| [[File:US-OF1A.svg|15px|center]] || [[First lieutenant#United States|First Lieutenant]] || 10th Cavalry, Regular Army || October 20, 1892\n|-\n| [[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|45px|center]] || [[Major (United States)|Major]] || [[Ordnance Corps (United States Army)|Chief Ordnance Officer]], [[United States Volunteers|Volunteers]] || August 18, 1898\n|-\n| [[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|45px|center]] || [[Major (United States)|Major]] || [[Adjutant General Corps|Assistant Adjutant General]], Volunteers || June 6, 1899 <br />(Reverted to permanent Regular Army rank of captain on July 1, 1901.)\n|-\n| [[File:US-O3 insignia.svg|35px|center]] || [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]] || Cavalry, Regular Army || February 2, 1901\n|-\n| [[File:US-O7 insignia.svg|35px|center]] || [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] || Regular Army || September 20, 1906\n|-\n| [[File:US-O8 insignia.svg|70px|center]] || [[Major general (United States)|Major General]] || Regular Army || September 25, 1916\n|-\n| [[File:US-O10 insignia.svg|140px|center]] || [[General (United States)|General]] || [[National Army (USA)|National Army]] || October 6, 1917\n|-\n| [[File:General of Armies insignia.svg|140px|center]] || [[General of the Armies]] || Regular Army || September 3, 1919<ref>{{cite journal |date=October 1, 1927 |title=The Legion's \"Second A. E. F.\" |url=https://books.google.com/?id=gk4_AAAAMAAJ&q=%22pershing%22+%22four%22+%22gold+stars%22&dq=%22pershing%22+%22four%22+%22gold+stars%22 |journal=The Literary Digest |volume=XCV |location=New York, NY |publisher=Funk & Wagnalls |page=11 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506052025/https://books.google.com/books?id=gk4_AAAAMAAJ&q=%22pershing%22+%22four%22+%22gold+stars%22&dq=%22pershing%22+%22four%22+%22gold+stars%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjD78iBiZPKAhWBKCYKHc2XC444ChDoAQhEMAc |archivedate=May 6, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |date=1924 |title=The Caduceus of Kappa Sigma |volume=40 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=khdMAAAAMAAJ&q=%22pershing%22+%22four%22+%22gold+stars%22&dq=%22pershing%22+%22four%22+%22gold+stars%22 |location=Charlottesville, VA |publisher=Kappa Sigma Fraternity |page=27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425164607/https://books.google.com/books?id=khdMAAAAMAAJ&q=%22pershing%22+%22four%22+%22gold+stars%22&dq=%22pershing%22+%22four%22+%22gold+stars%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjLu8-vkZPKAhXFLyYKHUqmBI44FBDoAQgpMAM |archivedate=April 25, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:General of Armies insignia.svg|140px|center]] || [[General of the Armies]] || Retired List || September 13, 1924<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/officialarmyregi1925unit#page/771/mode/1up Official Register of Commissioned Officers of the United States Army, 1925. pg. 772.]</ref>\n|}\n\n===Proposed six-star insignia===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! Insignia !! Rank !! Component !! Notes\n|-\n| [[File:6 Star.svg|95px|center]]\n| {{nowrap|[[General of the Armies]]}}\n| Retired List\n| Proposed six-star rank from December 14, 1944. (Congress never officially adopted the proposed six-star insignia for the General of the Armies rank.<ref>{{cite book |date=1987 |title=Army magazine |url=https://books.google.com/?id=bzdEAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22pershing%22+%22stimson%22+%22general+of+the+army%22&q=%22general+of+the+army+for+marshall%22 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=Association of the United States Army |page=60 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430071159/https://books.google.com/books?id=bzdEAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22pershing%22+%22stimson%22+%22general+of+the+army%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22general+of+the+army+for+marshall%22 |archivedate=April 30, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=International News Service |date=April 10, 1945 |title=Six Stars Urged for Gen. Pershing |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/58561781/?terms=%22pershing%22%2B%22six%2Bstars%22 |newspaper=The Evening News |location=Harrisburg, Pennsylvania |page=9 |url-access=subscription  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116131233/https://www.newspapers.com/image/58561781/?terms=%22pershing%22%2B%22six%2Bstars%22 |archivedate=January 16, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>)<br />\nGeneral of the Army was created as five-star rank by an Act of Congress on a temporary basis with the enactment of Public Law 78-482.<ref>{{cite book |last=Willbanks |first=James H. |date=2013 |title=Generals of the Army: Marshall, MacArthur, Eisenhower, Arnold, Bradley |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R9OkC2GUCmMC&pg=PA1914 |location=Lexington, KY |publisher=University Press of Kentucky |page=i |isbn=978-0-8131-4214-2}}</ref> The law creating the five-star rank stipulated that Pershing was to be considered senior to the five-star generals of World War II.<ref>{{cite book |last=Cray |first=Ed |date=2000 |orig-year=1990 |title=General of the Army: George C. Marshall, Soldier and Statesman |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gwq6WvWxe6oC&pg=PA491 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Cooper Square Press |page=491 |isbn=978-0-8154-1042-3}}</ref> The United States Infantry Association's ''Infantry Journal'' of 1949 states 'Presumably a \"General of the Armies\" could wear six stars if he was so-minded'.<ref>{{cite book |date=1949 |title=Infantry Journal |volume=64-65 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=AYrpAAAAMAAJ&q=%22john+j.+pershing%22+%22six+stars%22&dq=%22john+j.+pershing%22+%22six+stars%22 |location=Ft. Benning, GA |publisher=National Infantry Association |page=36}}</ref> Pershing's death before Congress decided whether to adopt the six-star insignia rendered the question [[Mootness|moot]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Oliver |first=Raymond |date=2007 |title=Why Is a Colonel Called a Kernal? the Origin of American Ranks and Insignia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9TcKmEs-I_UC&pg=PA53 |location=Tucson, AZ |publisher=Fireship Press |pages=52\u201353 |isbn=978-1-934757-59-8}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Assignment history===\n[[File:Johnpershing.jpg|thumb|225px|right|General Pershing lands in France in 1917]]\n* 1882: Cadet, United States Military Academy\n* 1886: Troop L, Sixth Cavalry\n* 1891: Professor of Tactics, University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln\n* 1895: 1st Lieutenant, 10th Cavalry Regiment\n* 1897: Instructor, United States Military Academy, West Point\n* 1898: Major of Volunteer Forces, Cuban Campaign, Spanish\u2013American War\n* 1899: Officer-in-Charge, Office of Customs and Insular Affairs\n* 1900: Adjutant General, Department of Mindanao and Jolo, Philippines\n* 1901: Battalion Officer, 1st Cavalry and Intelligence Officer, 15th Cavalry (Philippines)\n* 1902: Officer-in-Charge, Camp Vicars, Philippines\n* 1904: Assistant Chief of Staff, Southwest Army Division, Oklahoma\n* 1905: Military attach\u00e9, U.S. Embassy, [[Tokyo, Japan]]\n* 1908: Military Advisor to American Embassy, France\n* 1909: Commander of Fort McKinley, Manila, and governor of [[Moro Province]]\n* 1914: Brigade Commander, 8th Army Brigade\n* 1916: Commanding General, Mexican Punitive Expedition\n* 1917: Commanding General for the formation of the [[National Army (USA)|National Army]]\n* 1917: Commanding General, American Expeditionary Forces, Europe\n* 1921: Chief of Staff of the United States Army\n* 1924: Retired from active military service\n* 1925: Chief Commissioner assigned by the United States in the [[Tacna-Arica compromise|arbitration case]] for the provinces of [[Tacna]] and [[Arica]] between [[Peru]] and [[Chile]].\n\n===Honors and awards===\n[[File:Pershing WWI Ribbons.svg|thumb|center|325px|Pershing's ribbons as worn during World War I]]\n\n;Distinguished Service Cross Citation\n[[File:Army_distinguished_service_cross_medal.jpg|left|50px]]\n\nIn 1941 General Pershing was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]] for extraordinary heroism in action leading an against hostile Moros at Mount Bagsak, on the island of Jolo in the Philippines on June 15, 1913.<ref name=\"American Decorations 1941. pg. 1\">American Decorations. Supplement V. July 1, 1940 \u2013 June 30, 1941.  Government Printing Office.  Washington.  1941. pg. 1.</ref>\n\n;Citation:\n<blockquote>''For extraordinary heroism against hostile fanatical Moros at Mount Bagsak, Jolo, Philippine Islands on June 15, 1913. He personally assumed command of the assaulting line at the most critical period when only about 15 yards from the last Moro position.  His encouragement and splendid example of personal heroism resulted in a general advance and the prompt capture of the hostile stronghold.''<ref name=\"American Decorations 1941. pg. 1\"/></blockquote>\n\n====United States decorations and medals====\n<center>\n{|\n|+'''Pershing's medal ribbon board at retirement'''\n|-\n|[[File:Distinguished Service Cross ribbon.svg|110px]]\n|[[File:U.S. Army Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|110px]] \n|[[File:Silver Star ribbon.svg|110px]]\n|-\n|[[File:Indian Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|110px]]\n|[[File:Spanish Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|110px]] \n|[[File:Army of Cuban Occupation ribbon.svg|110px]]\n|-\n|[[File:Philippine Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|110px]]\n|[[File:Mexican Service Medal ribbon.svg|110px]] \n|{{ribbon_devices|number=4|type=service-star|other_device=bss|ribbon=World War I Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon_devices|number=4|type=service-star|other_device=bss|ribbon=World War I Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{ribbon_devices|number=4|type=service-star|other_device=bss|ribbon=World War I Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|[[File:Army of Occupation of Germany ribbon.svg|110px]] \n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n|[[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Army Distinguished Service Cross]] <br />(1941)\n|[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]] <br />(1918)\n|[[Silver Star]] <br />(1932)\n|-\n|[[Indian Campaign Medal]] <br />(1907)\n|[[Spanish Campaign Medal]] <br />(1905)<br />(with silver citation star upgraded to Silver Star decoration in 1932)\n|[[Army of Cuban Occupation Medal]] <br />(1915)\n|-\n|[[Philippine Campaign Medal]] <br />(1905)\n|[[Mexican Service Medal]] <br />(1917)\n|[[World War I Victory Medal (United States)|World War I Victory Medal]] <br />with 15 [[campaign clasp|battle clasps]] <br />(1919)\n|-\n|[[World War I Victory Medal (United States)|World War I Victory Medal]] <br />with 15 [[campaign clasp|battle clasps]] <br />(1919)\n|[[World War I Victory Medal (United States)|World War I Victory Medal]] <br />with 15 [[campaign clasp|battle clasps]] <br />(1919)\n|[[Army of Occupation of Germany Medal]] <br />(1941)\n|}\n</center>\n*Note: The dates indicated are the date the award was issued, not the date of action the award is based on.\n\nIn 1932, eight years after Pershing's retirement from active service, his silver citation star was upgraded to the [[Silver Star]] decoration. In 1941, he was retroactively awarded the [[Army of Occupation of Germany Medal]] for service in Germany following the close of World War I.  As the medal had a profile of Pershing on its obverse, Pershing became the only soldier in the history of the U.S. Army, and only one of four in the entire U.S. Armed Forces, eligible to wear a medal with his own likeness on it. Navy admirals [[George Dewey]], [[William T. Sampson]] and [[Richard E. Byrd]] were also entitled to wear medals with their own image on them.\n\n====International awards====\n<center>\n{|\n|+'''Ribbon board for foreign awards''' \n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"right\"|[[File:Order of the Bath (ribbon).svg|110px]] \n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"left\"|[[File:Legion Honneur GC ribbon.svg|110px]] \n|-\n|[[File:Medaille militaire ribbon.svg|110px]] \n|[[File:CroixdeGuerreFR-BronzePalm.png|110px]] \n|[[File:Grand Crest Ordre de Leopold.png|110px]] \n|[[File:BEL Croix de Guerre WW1 ribbon.svg|110px]] \n|-\n|[[File:POL Virtuti Militari Komandorski BAR.svg|110px]] \n|[[File:CZE Rad Bileho Lva 3 tridy BAR.svg|110px]]\n|[[File:Czechoslovak War Cross 1918 Ribbon.png|110px]]\n|[[File:Noribbon.svg|110px]]\n|-\n|[[File:Noribbon.svg|110px]] \n|[[File:GRE Order Redeemer 5Class.png|110px]] \n|[[File:Cavaliere di gran croce OMS BAR.svg|110px]] \n|[[File:Cavaliere di gran Croce Regno SSML BAR.svg|110px]] \n|-\n|[[File:JPN Kyokujitsu-sho blank BAR.svg|110px]] \n|[[File:Ordine San Pietro di Cetinje.gif|110px]]\n|[[File:ME Order of Danilo I Knight Grand Cross BAR.svg|110px]] \n|[[File:PAN Medalla de la Solidaridad.png|110px]]\n|-\n|[[File:PER Order of the Sun of Peru - Grand Cross BAR.png|110px]] \n|[[File:Order of Michael the Brave ribbon.svg|110px]] \n|[[File:Order of the Kara\u0111or\u0111e's Star with Swords rib.png|110px]] \n|[[File:VEN Order of the Liberator - Grand Cordon BAR.png|110px]] \n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|[[Knight Grand Cross]] of the [[Order of the Bath]] ([[UK|Britain]])\n|colspan=\"2\"|[[Grand Cross]] of the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur|Legion of Honor]] ([[France]])\n|-\n|[[M\u00e9daille militaire|Military Medal]] (France)\n|WWI [[Croix de Guerre]]<br />with bronze palm (France)\n|Grand Cross of the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)]]\n|WWI [[Croix de Guerre (Belgium)]]\n|-\n|[[Order Virtuti Militari]]<br />(2nd class\u2014Commander's Cross) ([[Poland]])\n|[[Order of the White Lion]]<br />(1st Class with Swords) ([[Czechoslovakia]])\n|[[Czechoslovak War Cross 1918]]\n|[[Grand Cordon]] of the Order of the Precious Jade ([[China]])\n|-\n|[[Order of the Golden Grain]]<br />(1st Class) (China)\n|[[Order of the Redeemer]] ([[Greece]])<br />''(degree unknown)''\n|Grand Cross of the [[Military Order of Italy|Military Order of Savoy]] ([[Italy]])\n|Grand Cross of the [[Order of Saints Maurice and Lazarus]] (Italy)\n|-\n|[[Order of the Rising Sun]] ([[Japan]]) ''(degree unknown)''\n|Medaille Obilitch, [[Milo\u0161 Obili\u0107]] medal instituted by [[Petar II Petrovi\u0107 Njego\u0161]] ([[Montenegro]])\n|Grand Cross of the [[Order of Prince Danilo I]] (Montenegro)\n|Medal of La Solidaridad (1st Class) ([[Panama]])\n|-\n|Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Sun (Peru)|Order of the Sun]] ([[Peru]])\n|[[Order of Michael the Brave]]<br />(1st Class) ([[Romania]])\n|Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Star of Karageorge]] with Swords ([[Serbia]])\n|Grand Cordon of the [[Order of the Liberator]] ([[Venezuela]])\n|}\n</center>\n\n[[File:Signature of John J. Pershing.jpg|thumb|285px|right|Signature of John Pershing as General of the Armies]]\n\n====Civilian awards====\n* [[Congressional Gold Medal]]\n* Thanks of the United States Congress\n* Distinguished Service Medal, [[American Legion]]\n* Special Medal of the Committee of the city of [[Buenos Aires]]\n* Induction into the [[Nebraska Hall of Fame]] (1963)\n\n[[File:General John J Pershing 8c 1961 issue.JPG|thumb|150px|General Pershing was honored with a U.S. postage stamp in 1961]]\n\n==Other honors and miscellany==\n{{see also|List of things named after John J. Pershing}}\n* Since 1930, the Pershing Park Memorial Association (PPMA), headquartered in Pershing's hometown of [[Laclede, Missouri]], has been dedicated to preserving the memory of General Pershing's military history.<ref>[http://www.pershingmuseum.com Pershing Memorial Museum and Leadership Archive official website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090712100623/http://www.pershingmuseum.com/ |date=July 12, 2009 }}</ref>\n* On November 17, 1961, the [[United States Postal Service]] released an 8\u00a2 [[Liberty Issue]] [[postage stamp]] honoring Pershing, shown at right.\n* Pershing was a [[Freemason]], a member of Lincoln Lodge No. 19, [[Lincoln, Nebraska]].<ref>Hamill, John et al. ''Freemasonry: A Celebration of the Craft''. JG Press 1998. {{ISBN|1-57215-267-2}}.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* Pershing is played by [[Milburn Stone]] in the 1955 film ''[[The Long Gray Line]]'', which was based on [[Martin Maher (soldier)|Martin 'Marty' Maher's]] [[autobiography]], ''Bringing Up the Brass: My 55 Years at West Point''<ref>Maher, Marty & Campion, Nardi Reeder  (1951) ''Bringing Up the Brass; My 55 Years at West Point'' New York: David Mackay Co.</ref> which depicts Pershing swearing Maher into the army.<ref>[[Bosley Crowther|Crowther, Bosley]], (February 11, 1955) [https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C02E1D8113FE33BBC4952DFB466838E649EDE? \"Screen: 'Long Gray Line' Tinted Green; Movie of West Point Honors Irish Hero\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116133133/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C02E1D8113FE33BBC4952DFB466838E649EDE%3F |date=January 16, 2017 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', Retrieved September 9, 2016</ref>\n*The [[actor]] [[Jody McCrea]] was cast as Lieutenant Pershing in the 1962 episode, \"To Walk with Greatness\", on the [[Television syndication|syndicated television]] [[anthology series]], ''[[Death Valley Days]]'', hosted by [[Stanley Andrews]]. In the story line, three outlaws endanger an Indian treaty, as Pershing sets forth to find the men. [[Frank Ferguson]] was cast as Colonel Carr.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0556911/?ref_=ttep_ep22|title=To Walk with Greatness on ''Death Valley Days''|publisher=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref>\n* Pershing appears as a character in ''The Friends of Pancho Villa'' (1996), a historical novel by [[James Carlos Blake]], as well as in ''Hard Magic: The Grimnoir Chronicles'' by [[Larry Correia]] (2011). He is mentioned frequently as one of the commanders in [[Harry Turtledove]]'s ''[[Southern Victory]]'' series in the volumes set during and shortly after the [[alternate history]] version of World War I, but his actual appearance is very brief.   He also has short appearances in the [[Anton Myrer]] novel, ''[[Once An Eagle]]''.\n* Pershing is played by [[Marshall Teague (actor)|Marshall Teague]] in the 1997 television miniseries ''[[Rough Riders (miniseries)|Rough Riders]]'', as the commander of the [[Buffalo Soldier]]s during the [[Battle of San Juan Hill]].\n* Pershing is played by [[Ron Perlman]] in the 2019 film ''The Great War''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[General Pershing WWI casualty list]]\n\n==References==\n'''Informational notes'''\n{{reflist|group=Notes}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n* Adas, Michael. \"Ambivalent Ally: American Military Intervention and the Endgame and Legacy of World War I\" ''Diplomatic History'